quickjs.library/--background--                  quickjs.library/--background--

    NAME
	quickjs.library -- QuickJS-ng JavaScript engine as an AmigaOS
	    shared library

    PURPOSE
	quickjs.library exposes the QuickJS-ng JavaScript engine
	(v0.12.1) through the standard AmigaOS shared library mechanism.
	Any Amiga program can OpenLibrary() it and get a full ES2020+
	JavaScript interpreter -- including async/await, modules,
	TypedArrays, Promises, Map, Set, BigInt, Proxy, WeakRef, and all
	the standard built-ins -- without having to statically link the
	500+ KB engine into every binary.

    AUTHOR
	Ported to AmigaOS by the nea-quickjs project, based on
	QuickJS-ng.  QuickJS was originally written by Fabrice Bellard;
	the -ng fork is community-maintained.

    VERSIONS
	The library ships in seven variants to match every 68k CPU/FPU
	combination.  The default file LIBS:quickjs.library is the
	020-soft build (runs on any 68020+ machine with or without an
	FPU).  For better math performance on FPU-equipped machines,
	replace it with one of the CPU-specific FPU variants:

	    quickjs.020fpu.library    68020 + 68881/68882 FPU
	    quickjs.020soft.library   68020, no FPU (default)
	    quickjs.040fpu.library    68040 with on-chip FPU
	    quickjs.040soft.library   68040 without FPU (or LC)
	    quickjs.060fpu.library    68060 with on-chip FPU
	    quickjs.060soft.library   68060 without FPU (or LC)

	All variants expose the exact same LVO table and can be swapped
	in place without recompiling clients.

    REQUIREMENTS
	AmigaOS 2.04 (V37) or higher.  Opens mathieeedoubbas.library
	(V34) and mathieeedoubtrans.library (V34) for all numeric work;
	these are standard on all AmigaOS installs from 2.04 onwards.

	For std.urlGet()/fetch() in JavaScript code, bsdsocket.library
	(AmiTCP, Miami, Roadshow, ...) must be available.  For HTTPS,
	AmiSSL must be installed.

    SEE ALSO
	--overview--, --calling_conventions--, exec.library,
	dos.library, bsdsocket.library


quickjs.library/--overview--                      quickjs.library/--overview--

    NAME
	--overview-- -- Using quickjs.library from C

    BASIC USAGE
	#include <proto/quickjs.h>

	struct Library *QuickJSBase;

	QuickJSBase = OpenLibrary("quickjs.library", 0);
	if (QuickJSBase) {
	    JSRuntime *rt = QJS_NewRuntime();
	    JSContext *ctx = QJS_NewContext(rt);

	    JSValue result;
	    QJS_Eval(&result, ctx, "2 + 2", 5, "<input>", 0);

	    const char *s = QJS_ToCStringLen2(ctx, NULL, &result, 0);
	    printf("Result: %s\n", s);    /* prints "4" */
	    QJS_FreeCString(ctx, s);

	    QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &result);
	    QJS_FreeContext(ctx);
	    QJS_FreeRuntime(rt);
	    CloseLibrary(QuickJSBase);
	}

    ARCHITECTURE
	The library owns a JSRuntime, which holds the engine's heap,
	GC, atom table, and class registry.  Inside a runtime you
	create one or more JSContexts; each context is a separate
	JavaScript global scope.  A single runtime may have many
	contexts that share atoms and classes.

	Every JSValue you receive from QJS_* calls is reference-counted.
	Release it with QJS_FreeValue() when you're done with it or
	memory will leak.

    FUNCTION CATEGORIES
	The 186 QJS_* functions fall into these broad groups:

	    Runtime management    --  creation/destruction, GC, memory
	    Context management    --  global scopes inside a runtime
	    Intrinsic setup       --  opt-in extra built-ins (Date,
				      RegExp, Promise, Proxy, Map/Set,
				      TypedArrays, BigInt, ...)
	    Evaluation            --  running JS source or bytecode
	    Value creation        --  wrapping C ints/strings/objects
				      as JSValue
	    Value conversion      --  extracting C types from JSValue
	    Type checking         --  IsArray, IsFunction, IsError, ...
	    Value lifecycle       --  FreeValue, DupValue
	    Properties            --  Get/Set/Has/Delete on objects
	    Object manipulation   --  prototype, freeze, seal, enumerate
	    Function calling      --  Call, Invoke, NewCFunction
	    Error handling        --  Throw, GetException
	    Atoms                 --  interned strings/symbols
	    JSON                  --  parse/stringify
	    Serialization         --  binary object format
	    ArrayBuffer/TypedArray
	    Promise system        --  creating/inspecting promises
	    Module system         --  import/export machinery
	    Class system          --  native class registration
	    Memory management     --  context-bound malloc/free
	    Standard library      --  std/os/bjson module init,
				      event-loop helpers

    SEE ALSO
	--calling_conventions--, QJS_NewRuntime, QJS_NewContext,
	QJS_Eval


quickjs.library/--calling_conventions-- quickjs.library/--calling_conventions--

    NAME
	--calling_conventions-- -- How the QJS_* API differs from
	    upstream quickjs.h

    BACKGROUND
	quickjs.library mechanically follows the upstream QuickJS-ng
	C API, but the AmigaOS shared library calling convention forces
	three systematic adaptations.  These three rules cover every
	difference between a QJS_* function and the upstream JS_*
	function with the same name.

    RULE 1: JSValue RETURN -> FIRST-ARGUMENT OUTPUT POINTER
	JSValue is a 12-byte struct on 68k (union of pointer, int,
	tag, padding).  AmigaOS library jump tables can only return
	32-bit values through D0, so any upstream function that
	returns a JSValue becomes a void function whose first argument
	is a pointer to caller-allocated JSValue storage.

	Upstream:    JSValue v = JS_NewString(ctx, "hello");
	Library:     JSValue v;  QJS_NewString(&v, ctx, "hello");

	The pointer must be non-NULL; its previous contents are
	overwritten without being freed.

    RULE 2: JSValueConst / JSValue PARAMETERS -> POINTERS
	For the same reason, any function that takes a JSValue or
	JSValueConst by value becomes one that takes a pointer:

	Upstream:    JS_FreeValue(ctx, val);
	Library:     QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &val);

	Upstream:    JSValue prop = JS_GetProperty(ctx, obj, atom);
	Library:     JSValue prop;
		     QJS_GetProperty(&prop, ctx, &obj, atom);

	The function does not take ownership of the reference; you
	still own `val` after the call.

    RULE 3: double PARAMETERS -> const double *
	AmigaOS library pragmas cannot assign a parameter to an FPU
	register, so double parameters are passed as pointers:

	Upstream:    JSValue n = JS_NewFloat64(ctx, 3.14);
	Library:     double d = 3.14;
		     JSValue n;  QJS_NewNumber(&n, ctx, &d);

	The pointer is const -- the callee only reads from it.

    EVERYTHING ELSE IS UNCHANGED
	Pointers, integers, enums, atoms, class IDs, and strings go
	through unchanged.  The semantics of every function match
	upstream QuickJS-ng exactly; only the parameter marshaling
	differs.

    LIMITATIONS
	Variadic functions (JS_ThrowTypeError et al with "fmt, ...")
	cannot cross the library boundary.  Non-variadic alternatives
	are provided where needed, e.g. throw the error yourself via
	QJS_Throw() on a pre-built Error object.

	Functions that require a FILE * (JS_DumpMemoryUsage) are not
	exposed.  Use QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage() and format the result
	yourself.

    SEE ALSO
	--overview--, QJS_FreeValue, QJS_NewNumber, QJS_NewStringLen


quickjs.library/QJS_NewRuntime               quickjs.library/QJS_NewRuntime

    NAME
	QJS_NewRuntime -- Create a new JavaScript runtime.

    SYNOPSIS
	rt = QJS_NewRuntime()
	D0

	JSRuntime *QJS_NewRuntime(VOID);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a new JavaScript runtime.  A runtime owns the engine's
	heap, garbage collector, atom table, and class registry.  You
	must create at least one JSContext inside it with
	QJS_NewContext() before you can evaluate any JavaScript.

	The runtime is allocated from the library's memory pool and
	lives until QJS_FreeRuntime() is called on it.

    INPUTS
	None.

    RESULT
	rt - Pointer to the new JSRuntime, or NULL if allocation
	    failed.  Pass to QJS_NewContext() and most other
	    runtime-scoped calls.

    EXAMPLE
	struct Library *QuickJSBase = OpenLibrary("quickjs.library", 0);
	JSRuntime *rt = QJS_NewRuntime();
	if (!rt) { CloseLibrary(QuickJSBase); return RETURN_FAIL; }
	JSContext *ctx = QJS_NewContext(rt);
	/* ... use ctx ... */
	QJS_FreeContext(ctx);
	QJS_FreeRuntime(rt);
	CloseLibrary(QuickJSBase);

    NOTES
	A JSRuntime is NOT reentrant.  Only one Task should call into
	a given runtime at a time.  For parallel JavaScript evaluation,
	create multiple independent runtimes.

	Default memory limit is unbounded.  Cap it with
	QJS_SetMemoryLimit() to protect against runaway scripts.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreeRuntime, QJS_NewContext, QJS_SetMemoryLimit,
	QJS_RunGC


quickjs.library/QJS_FreeRuntime             quickjs.library/QJS_FreeRuntime

    NAME
	QJS_FreeRuntime -- Destroy a JavaScript runtime.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_FreeRuntime(rt)
			A0

	VOID QJS_FreeRuntime(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	Releases all resources held by the runtime: its heap, atoms,
	classes, pending jobs, registered finalizers, and anything
	allocated through QJS_Malloc() and friends.  Any JSContexts
	still alive inside the runtime are freed first.

    INPUTS
	rt - A runtime pointer previously returned by QJS_NewRuntime().
	    May be NULL, in which case the call is a no-op.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSRuntime *rt = QJS_NewRuntime();
	/* ... work ... */
	QJS_FreeRuntime(rt);

    NOTES
	After this call, all JSContexts, JSValues, and other engine
	pointers originating from the runtime become invalid.  Using
	any of them is undefined behaviour.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewRuntime, QJS_FreeContext


quickjs.library/QJS_GetVersion               quickjs.library/QJS_GetVersion

    NAME
	QJS_GetVersion -- Return the QuickJS-ng engine version string.

    SYNOPSIS
	str = QJS_GetVersion()
	D0

	STRPTR QJS_GetVersion(VOID);

    FUNCTION
	Returns a pointer to a static, null-terminated ASCII string
	identifying the QuickJS-ng engine version compiled into this
	library (currently "0.12.1").

	This is the ENGINE version, not the AmigaOS port version.
	To see the port version, run AmigaDOS "version quickjs.library"
	or read LIBRARY_REVISION / LIBRARY_VERSION from the library
	base.

    INPUTS
	None.

    RESULT
	str - Pointer to a static string.  Do not modify or free.

    EXAMPLE
	printf("Using QuickJS-ng %s\n", QJS_GetVersion());

    SEE ALSO
	--background--


quickjs.library/QJS_SetMemoryLimit         quickjs.library/QJS_SetMemoryLimit

    NAME
	QJS_SetMemoryLimit -- Cap the heap size of a runtime.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetMemoryLimit(rt, limit)
			   A0  D0

	VOID QJS_SetMemoryLimit(JSRuntime *rt, ULONG limit);

    FUNCTION
	Limits the total bytes the runtime's garbage-collected heap
	may allocate.  When the limit is reached, allocation attempts
	return NULL and the engine throws an "out of memory" error
	into the current JavaScript context.

	Pass 0 (or a very large value) to disable the limit.

    INPUTS
	rt    - The runtime to limit.
	limit - Maximum heap size in bytes, or 0 for unlimited.
		The limit is applied immediately; if the current
		heap is already over the limit, the next allocation
		will fail.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	/* Limit to 4 MB -- plenty for most scripts */
	QJS_SetMemoryLimit(rt, 4 * 1024 * 1024);

    NOTES
	The memory limit counts engine-managed allocations only.
	Native buffers you allocate via AllocMem()/AllocVec() outside
	the engine are not tracked here.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewRuntime, QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage, QJS_RunGC


quickjs.library/QJS_SetMaxStackSize       quickjs.library/QJS_SetMaxStackSize

    NAME
	QJS_SetMaxStackSize -- Cap the JavaScript call stack depth.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetMaxStackSize(rt, stack_size)
			    A0  D0

	VOID QJS_SetMaxStackSize(JSRuntime *rt, ULONG stack_size);

    FUNCTION
	Sets the maximum C stack the engine is allowed to consume
	during JavaScript evaluation.  When the limit is reached, a
	RangeError "stack overflow" is thrown.

	The engine samples the current stack pointer to enforce this,
	so the limit is in bytes of the host C stack, not a count of
	JS frames.

	The default is a generous value chosen to handle deeply
	recursive scripts; lower it if you need to guarantee the
	caller's stack won't blow on a particular AmigaOS Task.

    INPUTS
	rt         - The runtime to configure.
	stack_size - Maximum stack usage in bytes; 0 disables the
		     check (not recommended on AmigaOS).

    RESULT
	None.

    NOTES
	Your AmigaDOS Stack setting, AmigaOS Task stack, and the
	Exec stack of whatever Task opens the library all apply.
	Deep recursion in JS only works if the underlying Task has
	enough stack, so "stack 65536" before running your program
	is often wise.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_UpdateStackTop, QJS_NewRuntime


quickjs.library/QJS_UpdateStackTop         quickjs.library/QJS_UpdateStackTop

    NAME
	QJS_UpdateStackTop -- Capture the current stack top for
	    stack-overflow detection.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_UpdateStackTop(rt)
			   A0

	VOID QJS_UpdateStackTop(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	The engine records a stack high-water mark at runtime
	creation and uses it to detect JS stack overflow.  If you
	call into the engine from a different AmigaOS Task (or after
	a long journey through foreign code that consumed a lot of
	stack), call this to re-synchronize the high-water mark
	against the current stack pointer.

    INPUTS
	rt - The runtime to update.

    RESULT
	None.

    NOTES
	Not needed in typical single-Task use.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetMaxStackSize


quickjs.library/QJS_RunGC                           quickjs.library/QJS_RunGC

    NAME
	QJS_RunGC -- Force a garbage collection cycle.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_RunGC(rt)
		  A0

	VOID QJS_RunGC(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	Runs a full garbage-collection cycle on the runtime's heap:
	collects cycles and reclaims memory occupied by unreachable
	objects.

	QuickJS uses reference counting as its primary strategy, so
	most garbage is freed immediately.  QJS_RunGC() is only
	needed to break reference cycles (objects that point at each
	other but are unreachable from the outside) or to reclaim
	memory after a burst of allocation before a memory-limit
	check.

    INPUTS
	rt - The runtime to collect.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	/* After parsing a big JSON blob, free any temporary cycles */
	QJS_RunGC(rt);

    NOTES
	GC is expensive.  Don't call this in tight loops.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetGCThreshold, QJS_GetGCThreshold,
	QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage


quickjs.library/QJS_GetGCThreshold       quickjs.library/QJS_GetGCThreshold

    NAME
	QJS_GetGCThreshold -- Read the current GC trigger size.

    SYNOPSIS
	threshold = QJS_GetGCThreshold(rt)
	D0                             A0

	ULONG QJS_GetGCThreshold(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the number of bytes of allocation that must elapse
	since the last GC before the engine automatically triggers a
	new one.

    INPUTS
	rt - The runtime to query.

    RESULT
	threshold - Threshold in bytes.  0 means GC is disabled.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetGCThreshold, QJS_RunGC


quickjs.library/QJS_SetGCThreshold       quickjs.library/QJS_SetGCThreshold

    NAME
	QJS_SetGCThreshold -- Configure when automatic GC triggers.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetGCThreshold(rt, threshold)
			   A0  D0

	VOID QJS_SetGCThreshold(JSRuntime *rt, ULONG threshold);

    FUNCTION
	Sets the allocation-since-last-GC threshold that triggers an
	automatic garbage collection.  Raise this to trade memory for
	speed; lower it to keep peak memory down on tight systems.

	Pass 0 to disable automatic GC entirely (manual QJS_RunGC()
	calls still work).

    INPUTS
	rt        - The runtime to configure.
	threshold - Bytes of allocation that trigger an auto-GC, or
		    0 to disable.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetGCThreshold, QJS_RunGC, QJS_SetMemoryLimit


quickjs.library/QJS_SetRuntimeInfo         quickjs.library/QJS_SetRuntimeInfo

    NAME
	QJS_SetRuntimeInfo -- Attach a diagnostic string to a runtime.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetRuntimeInfo(rt, info)
			   A0  A1

	VOID QJS_SetRuntimeInfo(JSRuntime *rt, CONST_STRPTR info);

    FUNCTION
	Stores a human-readable label on the runtime for use in GC
	dumps and memory-usage reports.  The string is not copied,
	so it must remain valid for the life of the runtime.

    INPUTS
	rt   - The runtime to label.
	info - Pointer to a static null-terminated string, or NULL
	       to clear.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage


quickjs.library/QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque     quickjs.library/QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque

    NAME
	QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque -- Retrieve the user opaque pointer.

    SYNOPSIS
	ptr = QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque(rt)
	D0                         A0

	APTR QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the opaque pointer previously stored with
	QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque().  The engine never dereferences this
	pointer; it is purely for the embedder's use.

    INPUTS
	rt - The runtime.

    RESULT
	ptr - The stored opaque, or NULL if none was set.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque, QJS_GetContextOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque     quickjs.library/QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque

    NAME
	QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque -- Attach an arbitrary pointer to a
	    runtime.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque(rt, opaque)
			     A0  A1

	VOID QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque(JSRuntime *rt, APTR opaque);

    FUNCTION
	Stores an opaque pointer on the runtime that can later be
	retrieved with QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque().  Typical uses:

	    * pointer to your application's state so C-callback
	      functions registered via QJS_NewCFunction2() can find
	      it via QJS_GetRuntime(ctx) + QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque();
	    * pointer to a logger, memory arena, etc.

	The engine treats the pointer as a black box -- it is never
	dereferenced and is not freed when the runtime is destroyed.

    INPUTS
	rt     - The runtime.
	opaque - Any pointer, or NULL.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque, QJS_SetContextOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_AddRuntimeFinalizer QJS_AddRuntimeFinalizer

    NAME
	QJS_AddRuntimeFinalizer -- Register a callback that fires
	    when the runtime is destroyed.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_AddRuntimeFinalizer(rt, finalizer, arg)
				A0  A1         A2

	VOID QJS_AddRuntimeFinalizer(JSRuntime *rt,
				     JSRuntimeFinalizer *finalizer,
				     APTR arg);

    FUNCTION
	Installs a finalizer function that will be invoked from
	inside QJS_FreeRuntime() just before the runtime's resources
	are released.  Use this to clean up state you attached via
	QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque() or any other per-runtime resources.

	Multiple finalizers can be registered; they fire in
	registration order.

    INPUTS
	rt        - The runtime.
	finalizer - Callback of type
			void (*)(JSRuntime *rt, void *arg);
		    Must not create new JSValues or call GC.
	arg       - User pointer passed verbatim to the callback.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreeRuntime, QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage   quickjs.library/QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage

    NAME
	QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage -- Fill a structure with current
	    memory statistics.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage(rt, s)
			       A0  A1

	VOID QJS_ComputeMemoryUsage(JSRuntime *rt, JSMemoryUsage *s);

    FUNCTION
	Walks the runtime's heap and fills the caller-supplied
	JSMemoryUsage structure with counts and sizes of each
	allocation category (objects, strings, atoms, shapes, ...).

	You can dump these fields directly or roll up your own report.

    INPUTS
	rt - The runtime to measure.
	s  - Pointer to a JSMemoryUsage structure (see <quickjs.h>
	     for layout).  The structure is overwritten entirely.

    RESULT
	None.  All values land in *s.

    NOTES
	Cheap enough to call per frame for a live memory display.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetMemoryLimit, QJS_RunGC


quickjs.library/QJS_SetDumpFlags           quickjs.library/QJS_SetDumpFlags

    NAME
	QJS_SetDumpFlags -- Enable/disable engine debug dumps.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetDumpFlags(rt, flags_ptr)
			 A0  A1

	VOID QJS_SetDumpFlags(JSRuntime *rt, const uint64_t *flags_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Configures which engine internals are dumped to stderr during
	execution: bytecode, GC activity, parse tree, atom table,
	etc.  The flag bits are the DUMP_* constants in <quickjs.h>.

	The flags are passed as a pointer because they live in a
	64-bit word that the AmigaOS calling convention cannot carry
	directly.

    INPUTS
	rt	  - The runtime.
	flags_ptr - Pointer to a uint64_t holding the OR-ed DUMP_*
		    constants.  Pass a pointer to zero to disable all
		    dumps.

    RESULT
	None.

    NOTES
	Useful only for engine debugging.  Normal applications should
	leave flags at zero.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetDumpFlags


quickjs.library/QJS_GetDumpFlags           quickjs.library/QJS_GetDumpFlags

    NAME
	QJS_GetDumpFlags -- Read the current engine dump flags.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetDumpFlags(rt, result_ptr)
			 A0  A1

	VOID QJS_GetDumpFlags(JSRuntime *rt, uint64_t *result_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Writes the currently-configured DUMP_* flag mask into the
	64-bit word pointed to by `result_ptr`.

    INPUTS
	rt	   - The runtime.
	result_ptr - Pointer to a uint64_t to receive the current
		     flags.

    RESULT
	None.  Flags land in *result_ptr.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetDumpFlags


quickjs.library/QJS_IsLiveObject           quickjs.library/QJS_IsLiveObject

    NAME
	QJS_IsLiveObject -- Check whether a given JSObject pointer
	    is still valid.

    SYNOPSIS
	live = QJS_IsLiveObject(rt, obj_ptr)
	D0                      A0  A1

	BOOL QJS_IsLiveObject(JSRuntime *rt, const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the object referenced by *obj_ptr has not
	been garbage-collected yet, FALSE otherwise.  Intended for
	diagnostic/debugging tooling; regular code should use
	reference counts rather than liveness checks.

    INPUTS
	rt	- The runtime.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to a JSValue containing an object.

    RESULT
	live - TRUE (non-zero) if still alive, FALSE otherwise.

    NOTES
	Do not use this to "repair" dangling references -- if a
	value might be dead, you've already lost the reference and
	need to fix the refcount handling.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_DupValue, QJS_FreeValue


quickjs.library/QJS_NewContext               quickjs.library/QJS_NewContext

    NAME
	QJS_NewContext -- Create a new JavaScript context (global
	    scope) inside a runtime.

    SYNOPSIS
	ctx = QJS_NewContext(rt)
	D0                   A0

	JSContext *QJS_NewContext(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a context with all standard intrinsics preinstalled
	(Object, Array, Function, Error, Math, JSON, RegExp, Date,
	Promise, Map/Set, TypedArrays, BigInt, Proxy, Reflect,
	performance, DOMException).  This is the normal entry point
	for most programs.

	If you need a context with only a subset of intrinsics, use
	QJS_NewContextRaw() instead and call individual QJS_Add*()
	functions for only the features you want.

	Multiple contexts in the same runtime share atoms and classes
	but have independent global objects; they cannot directly see
	each other's values without explicit transfer via
	QJS_WriteObject() / QJS_ReadObject().

    INPUTS
	rt - The host runtime.

    RESULT
	ctx - New context pointer, or NULL on allocation failure.

    EXAMPLE
	JSRuntime *rt = QJS_NewRuntime();
	JSContext *ctx = QJS_NewContext(rt);
	JSValue r;
	QJS_Eval(&r, ctx, "Math.PI", 7, "<input>", 0);
	/* ... */
	QJS_FreeContext(ctx);
	QJS_FreeRuntime(rt);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewContextRaw, QJS_FreeContext, QJS_DupContext,
	QJS_GetRuntime


quickjs.library/QJS_NewContextRaw         quickjs.library/QJS_NewContextRaw

    NAME
	QJS_NewContextRaw -- Create a context with no intrinsics
	    installed.

    SYNOPSIS
	ctx = QJS_NewContextRaw(rt)
	D0                      A0

	JSContext *QJS_NewContextRaw(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_NewContext() but no intrinsic objects are created.
	The returned context can evaluate plain expressions and
	function literals but has no global Object, Array, or Math
	unless you explicitly install them with QJS_AddBaseObjects()
	and the other QJS_Add*() functions.

	Use this to reduce memory footprint in applications that
	only need a minimal subset of JS, or to build sandboxed
	environments with a custom set of globals.

    INPUTS
	rt - The host runtime.

    RESULT
	ctx - New context pointer, or NULL on allocation failure.

    EXAMPLE
	JSContext *ctx = QJS_NewContextRaw(rt);
	/* Add only what we need */
	QJS_AddBaseObjects(ctx);
	QJS_AddJSON(ctx);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewContext, QJS_AddBaseObjects, QJS_AddJSON,
	QJS_AddEval


quickjs.library/QJS_FreeContext             quickjs.library/QJS_FreeContext

    NAME
	QJS_FreeContext -- Destroy a JavaScript context.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_FreeContext(ctx)
			A0

	VOID QJS_FreeContext(JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Releases all resources held by the context: its global
	object, loaded modules, pending jobs, and any JSValues that
	still reference it.  The parent JSRuntime is unaffected and
	can continue to host other contexts.

    INPUTS
	ctx - A context pointer previously returned by
	    QJS_NewContext() or QJS_NewContextRaw().  May be NULL.

    RESULT
	None.

    NOTES
	After this call, all JSValues bound to the context are
	invalid.  Free them with QJS_FreeValue() BEFORE calling
	QJS_FreeContext(), or the refcount updates will write into
	freed memory.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewContext, QJS_DupContext, QJS_FreeRuntime


quickjs.library/QJS_DupContext               quickjs.library/QJS_DupContext

    NAME
	QJS_DupContext -- Increment a context's reference count.

    SYNOPSIS
	ctx2 = QJS_DupContext(ctx)
	D0                    A0

	JSContext *QJS_DupContext(JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Adds one to the context's reference count and returns the
	same pointer.  Used when multiple owners need to keep a
	context alive; each owner must eventually call
	QJS_FreeContext() when done.

    INPUTS
	ctx - The context to retain.

    RESULT
	ctx2 - Same pointer as `ctx`, for chaining convenience.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewContext, QJS_FreeContext


quickjs.library/QJS_GetContextOpaque     quickjs.library/QJS_GetContextOpaque

    NAME
	QJS_GetContextOpaque -- Retrieve the context's user opaque
	    pointer.

    SYNOPSIS
	ptr = QJS_GetContextOpaque(ctx)
	D0                         A0

	APTR QJS_GetContextOpaque(JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Returns whatever was stored via QJS_SetContextOpaque().
	Engine never reads this pointer.

    INPUTS
	ctx - The context.

    RESULT
	ptr - Stored pointer, or NULL if none.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetContextOpaque, QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_SetContextOpaque     quickjs.library/QJS_SetContextOpaque

    NAME
	QJS_SetContextOpaque -- Attach an arbitrary pointer to a
	    context.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetContextOpaque(ctx, opaque)
			     A0   A1

	VOID QJS_SetContextOpaque(JSContext *ctx, APTR opaque);

    FUNCTION
	Stores an opaque pointer on the context.  Common uses:

	    * per-context state for C callbacks registered with
	      QJS_NewCFunction2();
	    * the parent application pointer when multiple contexts
	      represent independent windows/tasks/plugins.

	The engine never dereferences the pointer.

    INPUTS
	ctx    - The context.
	opaque - Any pointer, or NULL.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetContextOpaque, QJS_SetRuntimeOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_GetRuntime               quickjs.library/QJS_GetRuntime

    NAME
	QJS_GetRuntime -- Find the runtime that owns a context.

    SYNOPSIS
	rt = QJS_GetRuntime(ctx)
	D0                  A0

	JSRuntime *QJS_GetRuntime(JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the JSRuntime that hosts the given context.  Useful
	in C callbacks where you only received a JSContext but need
	to call runtime-scoped functions such as QJS_RunGC() or
	QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque().

    INPUTS
	ctx - A context pointer.

    RESULT
	rt - The owning runtime.  Never NULL for a valid context.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewContext, QJS_GetRuntimeOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_Eval                               quickjs.library/QJS_Eval

    NAME
	QJS_Eval -- Evaluate a JavaScript source string.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_Eval(result, ctx, input, input_len, filename, eval_flags)
		 A0      A1   A2     D0         A3        D1

	VOID QJS_Eval(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
		      CONST_STRPTR input, ULONG input_len,
		      CONST_STRPTR filename, ULONG eval_flags);

    FUNCTION
	Parses and executes a JavaScript source buffer, storing the
	result (or an exception) in *result.  The eval flags control
	parsing behaviour:

	    JS_EVAL_TYPE_GLOBAL (0)  -- classic-script mode
	    JS_EVAL_TYPE_MODULE (1)  -- ES module mode
	    JS_EVAL_FLAG_STRICT      -- force strict mode
	    JS_EVAL_FLAG_COMPILE_ONLY -- return the compiled function
					instead of executing it

	See <quickjs.h> for all JS_EVAL_* constants.

    INPUTS
	result	   - Output JSValue (see RULE 1 in calling_conventions).
	ctx	   - Target context.
	input	   - Source text (UTF-8).
	input_len  - Length of source in bytes, not counting a final
		     NUL.
	filename   - Name shown in stack traces.  Typically a filename
		     or "<input>".
	eval_flags - OR of JS_EVAL_* flags.

    RESULT
	None directly.  On success, *result holds the value of the
	last expression.  On failure, QJS_IsException(&*result) is
	true; retrieve the exception with QJS_GetException().

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue v;
	const char *src = "1 + 2 * 3";
	QJS_Eval(&v, ctx, src, strlen(src), "<input>", 0);
	if (!QJS_IsException(&v)) {
	    int n;
	    QJS_ToInt32(ctx, &n, &v);
	    printf("%d\n", n);   /* 7 */
	}
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &v);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_EvalSimple, QJS_EvalBuf, QJS_EvalFunction,
	QJS_DetectModule


quickjs.library/QJS_EvalSimple                   quickjs.library/QJS_EvalSimple

    NAME
	QJS_EvalSimple -- Evaluate a JavaScript expression with
	    default flags and no caller-managed result.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_EvalSimple(ctx, input, input_len)
	D0                  A0   A1     D0

	LONG QJS_EvalSimple(JSContext *ctx, CONST_STRPTR input,
			    ULONG input_len);

    FUNCTION
	Convenience wrapper around QJS_Eval() that discards the
	result value and returns only a pass/fail indication.  The
	filename is "<input>" and flags are 0 (classic script mode).

    INPUTS
	ctx	  - Target context.
	input	  - Source text (UTF-8).
	input_len - Length in bytes.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero if an exception was thrown.
	     The exception stays on the context; call
	     QJS_GetException() to retrieve it.

    EXAMPLE
	if (QJS_EvalSimple(ctx, "globalThis.counter = 0", 21) != 0) {
	    QJS_StdDumpError(ctx);
	}

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Eval, QJS_StdDumpError


quickjs.library/QJS_EvalBuf                         quickjs.library/QJS_EvalBuf

    NAME
	QJS_EvalBuf -- Evaluate JavaScript with std/os error handling.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_EvalBuf(ctx, input, input_len, filename, eval_flags)
	D0               A0   A1     D0         A2        D1

	LONG QJS_EvalBuf(JSContext *ctx, CONST_STRPTR input,
			 ULONG input_len, CONST_STRPTR filename,
			 ULONG eval_flags);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_Eval() but intended for stand-alone tools: on
	exception it automatically dumps the error via
	QJS_StdDumpError() and returns -1.  The evaluated value is
	discarded.

	Used by qjs.c for --eval and command-line scripts.

    INPUTS
	ctx	   - Target context.
	input	   - Source text.
	input_len  - Length in bytes.
	filename   - Name for stack traces.
	eval_flags - JS_EVAL_TYPE_* / JS_EVAL_FLAG_* mask.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, -1 on exception (already printed).

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Eval, QJS_StdDumpError, QJS_StdEvalBinary


quickjs.library/QJS_EvalFunction               quickjs.library/QJS_EvalFunction

    NAME
	QJS_EvalFunction -- Execute a previously-compiled function.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_EvalFunction(result, ctx, fun_ptr)
			 A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_EvalFunction(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			      const JSValue *fun_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Runs a function object that was produced by QJS_Eval() with
	the JS_EVAL_FLAG_COMPILE_ONLY flag, or deserialized via
	QJS_ReadObject().  This separates parsing from execution,
	allowing the same compiled code to be run in different
	contexts or stored in a file for later loading.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue for the return value.
	ctx	- Context to execute in.
	fun_ptr - Pointer to the compiled function JSValue.

    RESULT
	None.  *result holds the return value or an exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Eval, QJS_ReadObject, QJS_WriteObject


quickjs.library/QJS_DetectModule                 quickjs.library/QJS_DetectModule

    NAME
	QJS_DetectModule -- Heuristic check for ES module syntax.

    SYNOPSIS
	is_module = QJS_DetectModule(input, input_len)
	D0                           A0     D0

	BOOL QJS_DetectModule(CONST_STRPTR input, ULONG input_len);

    FUNCTION
	Scans the source for top-level `import` or `export` keywords.
	Returns TRUE if present, indicating the source should be
	evaluated with JS_EVAL_TYPE_MODULE.  FALSE means classic
	script mode is likely appropriate.

    INPUTS
	input	  - Source text.
	input_len - Length in bytes.

    RESULT
	is_module - TRUE if module syntax detected, else FALSE.

    NOTES
	Not a full parser; intended for the "autodetect" default used
	by qjs when the --script / --module flags are absent.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Eval


quickjs.library/QJS_NewNumber                       quickjs.library/QJS_NewNumber

    NAME
	QJS_NewNumber -- Wrap a C double as a JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewNumber(result, ctx, d_ptr)
		      A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_NewNumber(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			   const double *d_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a JS number value holding the double pointed to by
	`d_ptr`.  The double is passed by pointer per RULE 3 of the
	calling conventions: AmigaOS library pragmas cannot assign a
	parameter to an FPU register.

	The engine chooses the most compact representation: small
	integer values are stored as JS_TAG_INT, larger or
	fractional values become JS_TAG_FLOAT64.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	d_ptr  - Pointer to the double to wrap.  The pointer must
		 be non-NULL and the pointee remains the caller's
		 (not copied anywhere long-term).

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue pi;  double d = 3.14159265358979;
	QJS_NewNumber(&pi, ctx, &d);
	QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, global, "PI", &pi);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewBigInt64, QJS_ToFloat64, QJS_ToNumber


quickjs.library/QJS_NewBigInt64                   quickjs.library/QJS_NewBigInt64

    NAME
	QJS_NewBigInt64 -- Create a BigInt from a signed 64-bit
	    integer.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewBigInt64(result, ctx, v_ptr)
			A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_NewBigInt64(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			     const int64_t *v_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a BigInt JSValue from the 64-bit signed integer at
	`*v_ptr`.  Requires QJS_AddBigInt() to have been called on
	the context (automatic in QJS_NewContext()).

	Passed by pointer because an int64_t cannot fit in a single
	register on 68k.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	v_ptr  - Pointer to the 64-bit value.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewBigUint64, QJS_AddBigInt


quickjs.library/QJS_NewBigUint64                 quickjs.library/QJS_NewBigUint64

    NAME
	QJS_NewBigUint64 -- Create a BigInt from an unsigned 64-bit
	    integer.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewBigUint64(result, ctx, v_ptr)
			 A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_NewBigUint64(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			      const uint64_t *v_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_NewBigInt64() but for unsigned values.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	v_ptr  - Pointer to the 64-bit unsigned value.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewBigInt64, QJS_AddBigInt


quickjs.library/QJS_NewStringLen                 quickjs.library/QJS_NewStringLen

    NAME
	QJS_NewStringLen -- Create a JS string from a byte buffer.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewStringLen(result, ctx, str, len)
			 A0      A1   A2   D0

	VOID QJS_NewStringLen(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			      CONST_STRPTR str, ULONG len);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a JS string containing `len` bytes starting at `str`.
	The bytes are interpreted as UTF-8 and converted to the
	engine's internal string representation.

	This is the preferred primitive for strings that may contain
	embedded NULs or are not NUL-terminated.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	str    - Pointer to the UTF-8 bytes.  May contain NULs.
	len    - Number of bytes to read.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue greeting;
	QJS_NewStringLen(&greeting, ctx, "hello", 5);
	/* equivalent to QJS_NewString(&greeting, ctx, "hello") */

    NOTES
	For a NUL-terminated C string the upstream convenience wrapper
	JS_NewString() does not exist in the library interface;
	strlen() and call QJS_NewStringLen() yourself, or use
	QJS_NewAtomString() if you want an interned form.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewAtomString, QJS_ToCStringLen2, QJS_FreeCString


quickjs.library/QJS_NewAtomString               quickjs.library/QJS_NewAtomString

    NAME
	QJS_NewAtomString -- Create an interned string value.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewAtomString(result, ctx, str)
			  A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_NewAtomString(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			       CONST_STRPTR str);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a JS string from a NUL-terminated C string, passing
	through the atom table.  If the same string has been used
	before in this runtime the existing atom is reused, saving
	memory and making equality comparisons O(1).

	Prefer this over QJS_NewStringLen() for short, repeated
	strings like property keys.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	str    - NUL-terminated UTF-8 string.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue kind;
	QJS_NewAtomString(&kind, ctx, "mouse");
	QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, event, "kind", &kind);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewStringLen, QJS_NewAtom


quickjs.library/QJS_NewObject                       quickjs.library/QJS_NewObject

    NAME
	QJS_NewObject -- Create an empty plain object.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewObject(result, ctx)
		      A0      A1

	VOID QJS_NewObject(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a new object with Object.prototype as its prototype,
	equivalent to JavaScript's `{}`.  Populate it with
	QJS_SetPropertyStr() or QJS_DefinePropertyValue().

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue point, x, y;  double dx = 1.0, dy = 2.0;
	QJS_NewObject(&point, ctx);
	QJS_NewNumber(&x, ctx, &dx);
	QJS_NewNumber(&y, ctx, &dy);
	QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, &point, "x", &x);
	QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, &point, "y", &y);
	/* QJS_SetPropertyStr took ownership of x and y */

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewObjectClass, QJS_NewObjectProto, QJS_NewArray


quickjs.library/QJS_NewObjectClass           quickjs.library/QJS_NewObjectClass

    NAME
	QJS_NewObjectClass -- Create an object instance of a native
	    class.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewObjectClass(result, ctx, class_id)
			   A0      A1   D0

	VOID QJS_NewObjectClass(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				JSClassID class_id);

    FUNCTION
	Creates an object whose internal class is `class_id` and
	whose prototype is the class prototype previously installed
	with QJS_SetClassProto().  Used to implement native classes
	that pair a C struct (attached via QJS_SetOpaque()) with a
	JavaScript wrapper object.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	class_id - Class ID previously registered with
		   QJS_NewClassID() + QJS_NewClass().

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue handle;
	QJS_NewObjectClass(&handle, ctx, my_file_class_id);
	QJS_SetOpaque(&handle, my_FILE_ptr);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewClassID, QJS_NewClass, QJS_SetClassProto,
	QJS_SetOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_NewObjectProto           quickjs.library/QJS_NewObjectProto

    NAME
	QJS_NewObjectProto -- Create an object with a specific
	    prototype.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewObjectProto(result, ctx, proto_ptr)
			   A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_NewObjectProto(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				const JSValue *proto_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Creates an object whose [[Prototype]] is the value pointed
	to by `proto_ptr`.  Pass JS_NULL as *proto_ptr to create a
	prototype-less object (equivalent to
	`Object.create(null)`).

    INPUTS
	result	  - Output JSValue.
	ctx	  - Host context.
	proto_ptr - Pointer to the prototype JSValue.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewObject, QJS_SetPrototype, QJS_GetPrototype


quickjs.library/QJS_NewArray                         quickjs.library/QJS_NewArray

    NAME
	QJS_NewArray -- Create an empty array.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewArray(result, ctx)
		     A0      A1

	VOID QJS_NewArray(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a new Array object with length 0.  Use
	QJS_SetPropertyUint32() to append elements, or
	QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, &arr, "0", &v) / index strings for
	sparse arrays.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue arr, s;  int i;
	const char *names[] = {"red", "green", "blue"};
	QJS_NewArray(&arr, ctx);
	for (i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
	    QJS_NewAtomString(&s, ctx, names[i]);
	    QJS_SetPropertyUint32(ctx, &arr, i, &s);
	}

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewObject, QJS_SetPropertyUint32, QJS_GetLength


quickjs.library/QJS_NewSymbol                       quickjs.library/QJS_NewSymbol

    NAME
	QJS_NewSymbol -- Create a JS Symbol.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewSymbol(result, ctx, description, is_global)
		      A0      A1   A2           D0

	VOID QJS_NewSymbol(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			   CONST_STRPTR description, BOOL is_global);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a new Symbol.  If `is_global` is TRUE, the symbol is
	placed in (or fetched from) the global symbol registry --
	equivalent to `Symbol.for(description)`.  If FALSE, a unique
	local symbol is created -- equivalent to `Symbol(description)`.

    INPUTS
	result	    - Output JSValue.
	ctx	    - Host context.
	description - Description string for debugging, or NULL.
	is_global   - TRUE for Symbol.for(), FALSE for Symbol().

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	/* Look up Symbol.for('qjs.inspect') */
	JSValue sym;
	QJS_NewSymbol(&sym, ctx, "qjs.inspect", TRUE);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewAtomString


quickjs.library/QJS_NewDate                           quickjs.library/QJS_NewDate

    NAME
	QJS_NewDate -- Create a Date object from a millisecond epoch.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewDate(result, ctx, epoch_ms_ptr)
		    A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_NewDate(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			 const double *epoch_ms_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a JavaScript Date object representing the given
	milliseconds since the Unix epoch (1970-01-01 UTC).  The
	value is passed as a double pointer (RULE 3).

	Requires QJS_AddDate() to have been called on the context
	(automatic in QJS_NewContext()).

    INPUTS
	result	     - Output JSValue.
	ctx	     - Host context.
	epoch_ms_ptr - Pointer to milliseconds-since-epoch as double.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AddDate, QJS_IsDate


quickjs.library/QJS_ToString                         quickjs.library/QJS_ToString

    NAME
	QJS_ToString -- Convert any JSValue to its string form.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_ToString(result, ctx, val_ptr)
		     A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_ToString(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			  const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Invokes ECMAScript ToString() on the given value, producing
	a new string JSValue.  Numbers become their decimal form,
	objects invoke their toString() method, etc.

	To get the resulting bytes as a C string, call
	QJS_ToCStringLen2() on *result after this.  If you just want
	the C string form of the value, QJS_ToCStringLen2() can be
	called on the original value directly -- it performs the
	ToString conversion internally.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue holding the string.
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to convert.

    RESULT
	None.  On exception *result is an exception value.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ToCStringLen2, QJS_ToNumber, QJS_ToPropertyKey


quickjs.library/QJS_ToPropertyKey               quickjs.library/QJS_ToPropertyKey

    NAME
	QJS_ToPropertyKey -- Convert a value to a property key form.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_ToPropertyKey(result, ctx, val_ptr)
			  A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_ToPropertyKey(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			       const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Applies ECMAScript ToPropertyKey() to the value, producing
	either a string or a Symbol.  Intended for use before
	QJS_GetProperty() / QJS_SetProperty() if you're working with
	values that could be either form.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue.
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to convert.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ToString, QJS_ValueToAtom


quickjs.library/QJS_ToCStringLen2               quickjs.library/QJS_ToCStringLen2

    NAME
	QJS_ToCStringLen2 -- Extract a NUL-terminated C string from
	    a JSValue, with optional length.

    SYNOPSIS
	str = QJS_ToCStringLen2(ctx, plen, val_ptr, cesu8)
	D0                      A0   A2    A1       D0

	CONST_STRPTR QJS_ToCStringLen2(JSContext *ctx, size_t *plen,
				       const JSValue *val_ptr,
				       BOOL cesu8);

    FUNCTION
	Converts the value to a string via ECMAScript ToString() and
	returns a pointer to engine-owned UTF-8 bytes.  If `plen` is
	non-NULL, *plen receives the byte length (not counting the
	NUL terminator).

	The returned pointer is valid until you call
	QJS_FreeCString() with the SAME ctx and pointer.  You MUST
	eventually free every non-NULL result or memory leaks.

	The `cesu8` flag controls surrogate pair encoding: FALSE for
	standard UTF-8, TRUE to emit CESU-8 (encodes surrogate pairs
	as two 3-byte sequences instead of one 4-byte sequence).
	Use FALSE for virtually all AmigaOS work.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	plen	- Optional pointer to receive byte length, or NULL.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to stringify.
	cesu8	- TRUE for CESU-8 encoding, FALSE for strict UTF-8.

    RESULT
	str - Pointer to engine-owned UTF-8 bytes, or NULL on
	      conversion error (exception pending).  Caller must
	      release with QJS_FreeCString().

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue v;
	QJS_Eval(&v, ctx, "Math.PI", 7, "<input>", 0);
	const char *s = QJS_ToCStringLen2(ctx, NULL, &v, FALSE);
	if (s) {
	    printf("%s\n", s);
	    QJS_FreeCString(ctx, s);
	}
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &v);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreeCString, QJS_NewStringLen, QJS_ToString


quickjs.library/QJS_FreeCString                   quickjs.library/QJS_FreeCString

    NAME
	QJS_FreeCString -- Release a string returned by
	    QJS_ToCStringLen2().

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_FreeCString(ctx, ptr)
			A0   A1

	VOID QJS_FreeCString(JSContext *ctx, CONST_STRPTR ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Decrements the reference count on the string buffer handed
	back by QJS_ToCStringLen2().  Once the last user releases
	its reference, the bytes are freed.

    INPUTS
	ctx - Context that produced the string.  MUST match the
	      context passed to QJS_ToCStringLen2().
	ptr - Pointer previously returned; NULL is accepted and
	      ignored.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ToCStringLen2


quickjs.library/QJS_ToBool                             quickjs.library/QJS_ToBool

    NAME
	QJS_ToBool -- Test a value's truthiness.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_ToBool(ctx, val_ptr)
	D0                  A0   A1

	LONG QJS_ToBool(JSContext *ctx, const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Applies ECMAScript ToBoolean() to the value.  Falsy values
	(undefined, null, 0, -0, NaN, "", false) return 0; all
	others return 1.  Returns -1 if an exception was thrown
	during the conversion (rare -- usually only for values that
	invoke user code).

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value.

    RESULT
	result - 0 (falsy), 1 (truthy), or -1 (exception).

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ToInt32, QJS_ToFloat64


quickjs.library/QJS_ToInt32                           quickjs.library/QJS_ToInt32

    NAME
	QJS_ToInt32 -- Extract a signed 32-bit integer from a
	    JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_ToInt32(ctx, pres, val_ptr)
	D0               A0   A2    A1

	LONG QJS_ToInt32(JSContext *ctx, int32_t *pres,
			 const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Applies ECMAScript ToInt32() to the value and stores the
	result in *pres.  Fractional parts are truncated toward
	zero; out-of-range values are reduced mod 2^32.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	pres	- Output pointer for the 32-bit integer.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to convert.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero if an exception was thrown.

    EXAMPLE
	int n;
	JSValue v;
	QJS_Eval(&v, ctx, "2 + 2", 5, "<>", 0);
	if (QJS_ToInt32(ctx, &n, &v) == 0) printf("%d\n", n);
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &v);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ToInt64, QJS_ToFloat64, QJS_ToNumber


quickjs.library/QJS_ToInt64                           quickjs.library/QJS_ToInt64

    NAME
	QJS_ToInt64 -- Extract a signed 64-bit integer from a
	    JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_ToInt64(ctx, pres, val_ptr)
	D0               A0   A2    A1

	LONG QJS_ToInt64(JSContext *ctx, int64_t *pres,
			 const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Converts the value to an int64_t using ECMAScript
	ToIntegerOrInfinity() then clamping to the 64-bit range.
	BigInt values are accepted and converted losslessly if they
	fit.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	pres	- Output pointer for the 64-bit integer.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to convert.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ToInt32, QJS_ToFloat64, QJS_NewBigInt64


quickjs.library/QJS_ToFloat64                       quickjs.library/QJS_ToFloat64

    NAME
	QJS_ToFloat64 -- Extract a double from a JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_ToFloat64(ctx, pres, val_ptr)
	D0                 A0   A2    A1

	LONG QJS_ToFloat64(JSContext *ctx, double *pres,
			   const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Applies ECMAScript ToNumber() and stores the IEEE-754
	double in *pres.  String values are parsed; objects invoke
	their valueOf() / toString() methods.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	pres	- Output pointer for the double.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to convert.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on exception.

    NOTES
	On soft-float library builds, the resulting double is
	written to memory via mathieeedoubbas.library.  On FPU
	builds the compiler uses direct FPU stores.  Either way the
	caller never needs to involve an FPU register in the call.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ToInt32, QJS_ToNumber, QJS_NewNumber


quickjs.library/QJS_ToNumber                         quickjs.library/QJS_ToNumber

    NAME
	QJS_ToNumber -- Convert a value to a Number JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_ToNumber(result, ctx, val_ptr)
		     A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_ToNumber(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			  const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_ToFloat64() but returns the result as a fresh
	JSValue instead of a C double.  Useful when the next step
	is another JSValue-taking API.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue.
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value.

    RESULT
	None.  *result holds the number or an exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ToFloat64, QJS_NewNumber


quickjs.library/QJS_ToObject                         quickjs.library/QJS_ToObject

    NAME
	QJS_ToObject -- Apply ECMAScript ToObject() to a value.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_ToObject(result, ctx, val_ptr)
		     A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_ToObject(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			  const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Wraps primitive values in their corresponding wrapper
	objects: Number() for numbers, String() for strings, etc.
	Object values are returned unchanged (with a retained
	reference).  null and undefined throw a TypeError.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue.
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to convert.

    RESULT
	None.  *result holds the object form or an exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewObject


quickjs.library/QJS_GetGlobalObject             quickjs.library/QJS_GetGlobalObject

    NAME
	QJS_GetGlobalObject -- Retrieve the context's globalThis.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetGlobalObject(result, ctx)
			    A0      A1

	VOID QJS_GetGlobalObject(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Stores in *result the global object for the context --
	equivalent to the `globalThis` keyword in ES2020+.  All
	top-level declarations and intrinsic objects live as
	properties of this object.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.

    RESULT
	None.  *result holds a reference to the global object;
	release it with QJS_FreeValue() when done.

    EXAMPLE
	/* Install a native function as a global */
	JSValue global, fn;
	QJS_GetGlobalObject(&global, ctx);
	QJS_NewCFunction2(&fn, ctx, my_cfunc, "myFunc", 1,
			  JS_CFUNC_generic, 0);
	QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, &global, "myFunc", &fn);
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &global);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetPropertyStr, QJS_NewCFunction2


quickjs.library/QJS_FreeValue                       quickjs.library/QJS_FreeValue

    NAME
	QJS_FreeValue -- Release a reference to a JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, val_ptr)
		      A0   A1

	VOID QJS_FreeValue(JSContext *ctx, const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Decrements the reference count of the value pointed to by
	`val_ptr`.  When the count hits zero the value is reclaimed
	(strings are freed, objects are finalized, etc.).

	Every JSValue produced by a QJS_* function must eventually
	be released exactly once via QJS_FreeValue() (or
	QJS_FreeValueRT() if no context is available), or memory
	will leak.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to release.  Value must be
		  owned by the caller; after this call the caller
		  must not touch the JSValue again.

    RESULT
	None.

    NOTES
	Primitives (undefined, null, small ints, booleans) carry no
	refcount; calling this on them is a no-op.  You still should,
	so that conversion from a refcounted value is source-local.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreeValueRT, QJS_DupValue


quickjs.library/QJS_FreeValueRT                   quickjs.library/QJS_FreeValueRT

    NAME
	QJS_FreeValueRT -- Release a JSValue via runtime (no context
	    needed).

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_FreeValueRT(rt, val_ptr)
			A0  A1

	VOID QJS_FreeValueRT(JSRuntime *rt, const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Same as QJS_FreeValue() but takes a JSRuntime instead of a
	JSContext.  Use this in contexts where you only have a
	runtime pointer -- typically inside runtime-level finalizers
	registered via QJS_AddRuntimeFinalizer() or class GC hooks.

    INPUTS
	rt	- The runtime.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to release.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreeValue, QJS_DupValueRT


quickjs.library/QJS_DupValue                         quickjs.library/QJS_DupValue

    NAME
	QJS_DupValue -- Increment the reference count of a JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_DupValue(result, ctx, val_ptr)
		     A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_DupValue(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			  const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Produces a new JSValue that shares the same underlying
	object as *val_ptr and adds one to its reference count.
	Used when you need to hand a value to two owners (e.g.
	stashing a callback in a struct and returning it up the
	call chain).

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue (the duplicate).
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to duplicate.

    RESULT
	None.  Both *val_ptr and *result must eventually be released
	via QJS_FreeValue().

    EXAMPLE
	/* Remember a user callback in our struct */
	my->cb_dup = JS_UNDEFINED;
	{
	    JSValue dup;
	    QJS_DupValue(&dup, ctx, &user_cb);
	    my->cb_dup = dup;
	}

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreeValue, QJS_DupValueRT


quickjs.library/QJS_DupValueRT                     quickjs.library/QJS_DupValueRT

    NAME
	QJS_DupValueRT -- Duplicate a JSValue via runtime.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_DupValueRT(result, rt, val_ptr)
		       A0      A1  A2

	VOID QJS_DupValueRT(JSValue *result, JSRuntime *rt,
			    const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Runtime-scoped variant of QJS_DupValue() for use in
	finalizers and class GC hooks.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue.
	rt	- The runtime.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to duplicate.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_DupValue, QJS_FreeValueRT


quickjs.library/QJS_IsArray                           quickjs.library/QJS_IsArray

    NAME
	QJS_IsArray -- Test if a value is a JavaScript Array.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsArray(val_ptr)
	D0                   A0

	BOOL QJS_IsArray(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value is an Array instance (including
	arrays that inherit from Array.prototype and Proxy wrappers
	around arrays), FALSE otherwise.

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    EXAMPLE
	if (QJS_IsArray(&v)) {
	    int64_t len;
	    QJS_GetLength(ctx, &v, &len);
	    /* ... iterate ... */
	}

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewArray, QJS_GetLength


quickjs.library/QJS_IsFunction                     quickjs.library/QJS_IsFunction

    NAME
	QJS_IsFunction -- Test if a value is callable.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsFunction(ctx, val_ptr)
	D0                      A0   A1

	BOOL QJS_IsFunction(JSContext *ctx, const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value is a function object (ordinary,
	arrow, generator, async, or native C function), FALSE
	otherwise.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Call, QJS_IsConstructor, QJS_NewCFunction2


quickjs.library/QJS_IsConstructor               quickjs.library/QJS_IsConstructor

    NAME
	QJS_IsConstructor -- Test if a value can be called with
	    `new`.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsConstructor(ctx, val_ptr)
	D0                         A0   A1

	BOOL QJS_IsConstructor(JSContext *ctx,
			       const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value has a [[Construct]] internal
	method (ordinary functions, classes, some built-ins).
	Arrow functions are NOT constructors.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_CallConstructor, QJS_IsFunction


quickjs.library/QJS_IsError                           quickjs.library/QJS_IsError

    NAME
	QJS_IsError -- Test if a value is an Error instance.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsError(val_ptr)
	D0                   A0

	BOOL QJS_IsError(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value is an Error or one of its
	subclasses (TypeError, RangeError, SyntaxError, etc.).

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    NOTES
	A thrown exception is typically but not always an Error.
	Code like `throw "boom"` yields a thrown string, which is
	NOT an Error.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Throw, QJS_GetException, QJS_NewError


quickjs.library/QJS_IsArrayBuffer               quickjs.library/QJS_IsArrayBuffer

    NAME
	QJS_IsArrayBuffer -- Test if a value is an ArrayBuffer.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsArrayBuffer(val_ptr)
	D0                         A0

	BOOL QJS_IsArrayBuffer(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE for an ArrayBuffer or SharedArrayBuffer, FALSE
	for typed-array views over a buffer or any other value.

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy, QJS_GetArrayBuffer


quickjs.library/QJS_IsDate                             quickjs.library/QJS_IsDate

    NAME
	QJS_IsDate -- Test if a value is a Date.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsDate(val_ptr)
	D0                  A0

	BOOL QJS_IsDate(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value is a Date instance.

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewDate, QJS_AddDate


quickjs.library/QJS_IsRegExp                         quickjs.library/QJS_IsRegExp

    NAME
	QJS_IsRegExp -- Test if a value is a RegExp.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsRegExp(val_ptr)
	D0                    A0

	BOOL QJS_IsRegExp(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value is a RegExp instance.

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AddRegExp


quickjs.library/QJS_IsMap                               quickjs.library/QJS_IsMap

    NAME
	QJS_IsMap -- Test if a value is a Map.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsMap(val_ptr)
	D0                 A0

	BOOL QJS_IsMap(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value is a Map instance.  WeakMap
	instances also return TRUE; distinguish via the prototype
	chain if needed.

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_IsSet, QJS_AddMapSet


quickjs.library/QJS_IsSet                               quickjs.library/QJS_IsSet

    NAME
	QJS_IsSet -- Test if a value is a Set.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsSet(val_ptr)
	D0                 A0

	BOOL QJS_IsSet(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value is a Set instance.  WeakSet
	instances also return TRUE.

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_IsMap, QJS_AddMapSet


quickjs.library/QJS_IsPromise                       quickjs.library/QJS_IsPromise

    NAME
	QJS_IsPromise -- Test if a value is a Promise.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsPromise(val_ptr)
	D0                     A0

	BOOL QJS_IsPromise(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the value is a genuine Promise instance
	(checks for the internal [[PromiseState]] slot).  Thenable
	objects that merely have a .then method are NOT promises
	by this test.

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewPromiseCapability, QJS_PromiseState,
	QJS_PromiseResult


quickjs.library/QJS_IsExtensible                 quickjs.library/QJS_IsExtensible

    NAME
	QJS_IsExtensible -- Check whether new properties can be
	    added to an object.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsExtensible(ctx, obj_ptr)
	D0                        A0   A1

	LONG QJS_IsExtensible(JSContext *ctx,
			      const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns 1 if the object is extensible, 0 if sealed or
	frozen, -1 on exception.  Non-objects return 0.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object to test.

    RESULT
	result - 1 (extensible), 0 (not), or -1 (exception).

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_PreventExtensions, QJS_SealObject, QJS_FreezeObject


quickjs.library/QJS_IsInstanceOf                 quickjs.library/QJS_IsInstanceOf

    NAME
	QJS_IsInstanceOf -- Check prototype-chain membership.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsInstanceOf(ctx, val_ptr, obj_ptr)
	D0                        A0   A1       A2

	LONG QJS_IsInstanceOf(JSContext *ctx,
			      const JSValue *val_ptr,
			      const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to `val instanceof obj` in JavaScript: returns
	1 if val's prototype chain contains obj's prototype (or if
	obj has a [[HasInstance]] method that returns true), 0
	otherwise, -1 on exception.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the value to test.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the constructor (or object with
		  Symbol.hasInstance).

    RESULT
	result - 1, 0, or -1.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetPrototype, QJS_SetPrototype


quickjs.library/QJS_IsEqual                           quickjs.library/QJS_IsEqual

    NAME
	QJS_IsEqual -- Loose equality (`==`) comparison.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsEqual(ctx, op1_ptr, op2_ptr)
	D0                   A0   A1       A2

	LONG QJS_IsEqual(JSContext *ctx,
			 const JSValue *op1_ptr,
			 const JSValue *op2_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Applies ECMAScript Abstract Equality (== operator) to the
	two values.  Performs type coercion between numbers, strings
	and booleans; special cases for null/undefined.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	op1_ptr - Pointer to the left operand.
	op2_ptr - Pointer to the right operand.

    RESULT
	result - 1 if equal, 0 if not, -1 on exception (coercion
	         may invoke user code).

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_IsStrictEqual, QJS_IsSameValue


quickjs.library/QJS_IsStrictEqual               quickjs.library/QJS_IsStrictEqual

    NAME
	QJS_IsStrictEqual -- Strict equality (`===`) comparison.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsStrictEqual(ctx, op1_ptr, op2_ptr)
	D0                         A0   A1       A2

	BOOL QJS_IsStrictEqual(JSContext *ctx,
			       const JSValue *op1_ptr,
			       const JSValue *op2_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Applies ECMAScript Strict Equality (=== operator).  No type
	coercion; NaN is not equal to itself; +0 equals -0.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	op1_ptr - Pointer to the left operand.
	op2_ptr - Pointer to the right operand.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_IsEqual, QJS_IsSameValue, QJS_IsSameValueZero


quickjs.library/QJS_IsSameValue                   quickjs.library/QJS_IsSameValue

    NAME
	QJS_IsSameValue -- Object.is() equality.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsSameValue(ctx, op1_ptr, op2_ptr)
	D0                       A0   A1       A2

	BOOL QJS_IsSameValue(JSContext *ctx,
			     const JSValue *op1_ptr,
			     const JSValue *op2_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Applies the SameValue algorithm, equivalent to JavaScript
	Object.is().  Unlike `===`, NaN IS equal to NaN and +0 is
	NOT equal to -0.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	op1_ptr - Pointer to the left operand.
	op2_ptr - Pointer to the right operand.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_IsStrictEqual, QJS_IsSameValueZero


quickjs.library/QJS_IsSameValueZero           quickjs.library/QJS_IsSameValueZero

    NAME
	QJS_IsSameValueZero -- SameValueZero equality (used by
	    Map/Set).

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsSameValueZero(ctx, op1_ptr, op2_ptr)
	D0                           A0   A1       A2

	BOOL QJS_IsSameValueZero(JSContext *ctx,
				 const JSValue *op1_ptr,
				 const JSValue *op2_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_IsSameValue() but treats +0 and -0 as equal.  This
	is the equality used by Map keys, Set elements and
	Array.prototype.includes().

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	op1_ptr - Pointer to the left operand.
	op2_ptr - Pointer to the right operand.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_IsStrictEqual, QJS_IsSameValue


quickjs.library/QJS_GetProperty                   quickjs.library/QJS_GetProperty

    NAME
	QJS_GetProperty -- Read a property by atom key.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetProperty(result, ctx, this_ptr, prop)
			A0      A1   A2        D0

	VOID QJS_GetProperty(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			     const JSValue *this_ptr, JSAtom prop);

    FUNCTION
	Reads `this[prop]` where `prop` is a pre-interned JSAtom.
	Honours getters, proxy traps and the prototype chain.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the object to read from.
	prop	 - Atom key.

    RESULT
	None.  *result is undefined if the property does not exist,
	the value if it does, or an exception on error.

    EXAMPLE
	JSAtom name = QJS_NewAtom(ctx, "length");
	JSValue len;
	QJS_GetProperty(&len, ctx, &arr, name);
	QJS_FreeAtom(ctx, name);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetPropertyStr, QJS_GetPropertyUint32, QJS_SetProperty


quickjs.library/QJS_GetPropertyUint32       quickjs.library/QJS_GetPropertyUint32

    NAME
	QJS_GetPropertyUint32 -- Read an array element by numeric
	    index.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetPropertyUint32(result, ctx, this_ptr, idx)
			      A0      A1   A2        D0

	VOID QJS_GetPropertyUint32(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				   const JSValue *this_ptr,
				   ULONG idx);

    FUNCTION
	Reads `this[idx]` as an indexed access.  Optimized for
	Array and typed-array paths.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the object.
	idx	 - Unsigned 32-bit index.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetPropertyUint32, QJS_GetLength


quickjs.library/QJS_GetPropertyStr             quickjs.library/QJS_GetPropertyStr

    NAME
	QJS_GetPropertyStr -- Read a property by C-string key.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetPropertyStr(result, ctx, this_ptr, prop_str)
			   A0      A1   A2        A3

	VOID QJS_GetPropertyStr(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				const JSValue *this_ptr,
				CONST_STRPTR prop_str);

    FUNCTION
	Convenience wrapper that creates an atom from the
	NUL-terminated C string, calls QJS_GetProperty(), then
	releases the atom.  Good for one-shot lookups; cache an
	atom yourself if you'll read the same key many times.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the object.
	prop_str - NUL-terminated property name (UTF-8).

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue status;
	QJS_GetPropertyStr(&status, ctx, &response, "status");

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetProperty, QJS_SetPropertyStr


quickjs.library/QJS_GetPropertyInt64         quickjs.library/QJS_GetPropertyInt64

    NAME
	QJS_GetPropertyInt64 -- Read an array element by 64-bit
	    index.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetPropertyInt64(result, ctx, this_ptr, idx)
			     A0      A1   A2        D0

	VOID QJS_GetPropertyInt64(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				  const JSValue *this_ptr,
				  LONG idx);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_GetPropertyUint32() but accepts a 64-bit signed
	index.  Useful for very large TypedArrays and BigInt-indexed
	structures.

	Note: the index is passed through D0 truncated to 32 bits in
	the AmigaOS calling convention; indices above 2^31-1 are not
	reachable via this LVO.  Use QJS_GetProperty() with an atom
	for truly 64-bit indices.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the object.
	idx	 - Signed index (effectively 32-bit on 68k).

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetPropertyUint32, QJS_GetProperty


quickjs.library/QJS_SetProperty                   quickjs.library/QJS_SetProperty

    NAME
	QJS_SetProperty -- Write a property by atom key.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SetProperty(ctx, this_ptr, prop, val_ptr)
	D0                   A0   A1        D0    A2

	LONG QJS_SetProperty(JSContext *ctx,
			     const JSValue *this_ptr,
			     JSAtom prop, const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Writes `this[prop] = *val_ptr`.  Honours setters and proxy
	traps.  Takes ownership of the value reference -- after this
	call, *val_ptr no longer needs a QJS_FreeValue().

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the target object.
	prop	 - Atom key.
	val_ptr  - Pointer to the value to store.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, 0 if the property could not be set
	     (e.g. frozen object, strict-mode refusal), -1 on
	     exception.

    NOTES
	This differs from other SetProperty APIs in that ownership
	transfer is the norm, matching upstream QuickJS-ng
	semantics.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetProperty, QJS_SetPropertyStr, QJS_DefinePropertyValue


quickjs.library/QJS_SetPropertyUint32       quickjs.library/QJS_SetPropertyUint32

    NAME
	QJS_SetPropertyUint32 -- Write an array element by numeric
	    index.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SetPropertyUint32(ctx, this_ptr, idx, val_ptr)
	D0                         A0   A1        D0   A2

	LONG QJS_SetPropertyUint32(JSContext *ctx,
				   const JSValue *this_ptr,
				   ULONG idx,
				   const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Stores `this[idx] = *val_ptr`.  Takes ownership of the
	value reference.  Extends Array length if idx >= current
	length.

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the array/object.
	idx	 - Unsigned 32-bit index.
	val_ptr  - Pointer to the value to store.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, 0 if refused, -1 on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetPropertyUint32, QJS_NewArray


quickjs.library/QJS_SetPropertyStr             quickjs.library/QJS_SetPropertyStr

    NAME
	QJS_SetPropertyStr -- Write a property by C-string key.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, this_ptr, prop_str, val_ptr)
	D0                      A0   A1        A2        A3

	LONG QJS_SetPropertyStr(JSContext *ctx,
				const JSValue *this_ptr,
				CONST_STRPTR prop_str,
				const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Convenience wrapper around QJS_SetProperty() with a
	C-string key.  Takes ownership of the value reference.

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the target object.
	prop_str - NUL-terminated property name.
	val_ptr  - Pointer to the value to store.

    RESULT
	rc - 1/0/-1 as QJS_SetProperty().

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue n;  int v = 42;
	QJS_NewNumber(&n, ctx, &(double){(double)v});
	QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, &obj, "count", &n);
	/* Do NOT call QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &n) -- ownership was
	   transferred. */

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetPropertyStr, QJS_SetProperty


quickjs.library/QJS_HasProperty                   quickjs.library/QJS_HasProperty

    NAME
	QJS_HasProperty -- Test whether a property exists.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_HasProperty(ctx, this_ptr, prop)
	D0                   A0   A1        D0

	LONG QJS_HasProperty(JSContext *ctx,
			     const JSValue *this_ptr, JSAtom prop);

    FUNCTION
	Returns 1 if the property exists on the object or anywhere
	in its prototype chain, 0 if not, -1 on exception
	(proxy traps may throw).

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the object.
	prop	 - Atom key.

    RESULT
	rc - 1, 0, or -1.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetProperty, QJS_DeleteProperty


quickjs.library/QJS_DeleteProperty             quickjs.library/QJS_DeleteProperty

    NAME
	QJS_DeleteProperty -- Remove a property from an object.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_DeleteProperty(ctx, obj_ptr, prop, flags)
	D0                      A0   A1       D0    D1

	LONG QJS_DeleteProperty(JSContext *ctx,
				const JSValue *obj_ptr,
				JSAtom prop, ULONG flags);

    FUNCTION
	Deletes `obj[prop]`.  The `flags` argument controls strict
	behaviour: pass JS_PROP_THROW to raise a TypeError if the
	property exists but cannot be deleted (i.e. is
	non-configurable), or 0 for the default silent refusal.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object.
	prop	- Atom key.
	flags	- 0 or JS_PROP_THROW.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, 0 if refused without throwing, -1 on
	     exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_HasProperty, QJS_FreezeObject


quickjs.library/QJS_SetPrototype                   quickjs.library/QJS_SetPrototype

    NAME
	QJS_SetPrototype -- Change an object's [[Prototype]].

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SetPrototype(ctx, obj_ptr, proto_ptr)
	D0                    A0   A1       A2

	LONG QJS_SetPrototype(JSContext *ctx,
			      const JSValue *obj_ptr,
			      const JSValue *proto_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Sets the [[Prototype]] of `*obj_ptr` to `*proto_ptr`
	(or null if *proto_ptr is JS_NULL).  Equivalent to
	Object.setPrototypeOf().

    INPUTS
	ctx	  - Host context.
	obj_ptr	  - Pointer to the object.
	proto_ptr - Pointer to the new prototype.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, 0 if refused (non-extensible object),
	     -1 on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetPrototype, QJS_NewObjectProto


quickjs.library/QJS_GetPrototype                   quickjs.library/QJS_GetPrototype

    NAME
	QJS_GetPrototype -- Read an object's [[Prototype]].

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetPrototype(result, ctx, val_ptr)
			 A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_GetPrototype(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			      const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to Object.getPrototypeOf(*val_ptr).  Returns
	JS_NULL for prototype-less objects.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue (the prototype).
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the object.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetPrototype, QJS_NewObjectProto


quickjs.library/QJS_GetLength                       quickjs.library/QJS_GetLength

    NAME
	QJS_GetLength -- Read an object's `length` property as
	    int64.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_GetLength(ctx, obj_ptr, pres)
	D0                 A0   A1       A2

	LONG QJS_GetLength(JSContext *ctx,
			   const JSValue *obj_ptr, int64_t *pres);

    FUNCTION
	Reads `obj.length` and converts it to a 64-bit signed
	integer via ToLength().  Commonly used with arrays and
	array-like objects.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object.
	pres	- Output pointer for the length.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetLength, QJS_GetPropertyStr


quickjs.library/QJS_SetLength                       quickjs.library/QJS_SetLength

    NAME
	QJS_SetLength -- Set an object's `length` property.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SetLength(ctx, obj_ptr, len)
	D0                 A0   A1       D0

	LONG QJS_SetLength(JSContext *ctx,
			   const JSValue *obj_ptr, LONG len);

    FUNCTION
	Sets `obj.length = len`.  For Arrays this truncates or
	extends the array; for other objects it simply assigns the
	property.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object.
	len	- New length.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetLength, QJS_NewArray


quickjs.library/QJS_PreventExtensions         quickjs.library/QJS_PreventExtensions

    NAME
	QJS_PreventExtensions -- Prevent new properties from being
	    added to an object.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_PreventExtensions(ctx, obj_ptr)
	D0                         A0   A1

	LONG QJS_PreventExtensions(JSContext *ctx,
				   const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to Object.preventExtensions().  After this call,
	attempts to add new properties fail (silently or throw
	depending on strict mode).  Existing properties can still
	be modified or deleted.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, -1 on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_IsExtensible, QJS_SealObject, QJS_FreezeObject


quickjs.library/QJS_SealObject                     quickjs.library/QJS_SealObject

    NAME
	QJS_SealObject -- Seal an object (prevent extensions +
	    mark all properties non-configurable).

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SealObject(ctx, obj_ptr)
	D0                  A0   A1

	LONG QJS_SealObject(JSContext *ctx,
			    const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to Object.seal().  Properties can still be
	written but not added, removed, or reconfigured.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, -1 on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreezeObject, QJS_PreventExtensions


quickjs.library/QJS_FreezeObject                 quickjs.library/QJS_FreezeObject

    NAME
	QJS_FreezeObject -- Freeze an object (seal + mark all
	    properties read-only).

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_FreezeObject(ctx, obj_ptr)
	D0                    A0   A1

	LONG QJS_FreezeObject(JSContext *ctx,
			      const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to Object.freeze().  The object becomes fully
	immutable: no new properties, no deletions, no writes to
	existing properties.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, -1 on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SealObject, QJS_PreventExtensions


quickjs.library/QJS_DefinePropertyValue     quickjs.library/QJS_DefinePropertyValue

    NAME
	QJS_DefinePropertyValue -- Define a data property with
	    explicit attributes.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_DefinePropertyValue(ctx, this_ptr, prop, val_ptr,
				     flags)
	D0                           A0   A1        D0    A2
				     D1

	LONG QJS_DefinePropertyValue(JSContext *ctx,
				     const JSValue *this_ptr,
				     JSAtom prop,
				     const JSValue *val_ptr,
				     ULONG flags);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to Object.defineProperty() with a data
	descriptor.  The `flags` combine JS_PROP_WRITABLE,
	JS_PROP_ENUMERABLE, JS_PROP_CONFIGURABLE and
	JS_PROP_THROW.  Takes ownership of *val_ptr.

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the target object.
	prop	 - Atom key.
	val_ptr  - Pointer to the value.
	flags	 - OR of JS_PROP_* constants.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, 0 if refused, -1 on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr, QJS_DefinePropertyValueUint32,
	QJS_SetProperty


quickjs.library/QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr

    NAME
	QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr -- defineProperty with a
	    C-string key.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr(ctx, this_ptr, val_ptr,
					prop_str, flags)
	D0                              A0   A1        A2
					A3        D0

	LONG QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr(JSContext *ctx,
					const JSValue *this_ptr,
					const JSValue *val_ptr,
					CONST_STRPTR prop_str,
					ULONG flags);

    FUNCTION
	Same as QJS_DefinePropertyValue() but takes a C-string key
	for convenience.  Note the argument order: the value comes
	before the property name.

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the target object.
	val_ptr  - Pointer to the value.
	prop_str - NUL-terminated property name.
	flags	 - OR of JS_PROP_* constants.

    RESULT
	rc - 1/0/-1.

    EXAMPLE
	/* Install a non-enumerable, read-only property */
	QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr(ctx, &obj, &val, "kind",
	    JS_PROP_CONFIGURABLE);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_DefinePropertyValue, QJS_SetPropertyStr


quickjs.library/QJS_DefinePropertyValueUint32 QJS_DefinePropertyValueUint32

    NAME
	QJS_DefinePropertyValueUint32 -- defineProperty with a
	    numeric index key.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_DefinePropertyValueUint32(ctx, this_ptr, idx,
					   val_ptr, flags)
	D0                                 A0   A1        D0
					   A2       D1

	LONG QJS_DefinePropertyValueUint32(JSContext *ctx,
					const JSValue *this_ptr,
					ULONG idx,
					const JSValue *val_ptr,
					ULONG flags);

    FUNCTION
	Same as QJS_DefinePropertyValue() but with a numeric index
	key.

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the target object.
	idx	 - Unsigned 32-bit index.
	val_ptr  - Pointer to the value.
	flags	 - OR of JS_PROP_* constants.

    RESULT
	rc - 1/0/-1.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_DefinePropertyValue, QJS_SetPropertyUint32


quickjs.library/QJS_SetOpaque                       quickjs.library/QJS_SetOpaque

    NAME
	QJS_SetOpaque -- Attach a C pointer to a class instance.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetOpaque(obj_ptr, opaque)
		      A1       A0

	VOID QJS_SetOpaque(const JSValue *obj_ptr, APTR opaque);

    FUNCTION
	Stores a C pointer inside the JS object's opaque slot.
	Used to bind a native struct to a JavaScript wrapper
	created with QJS_NewObjectClass().

	The object must be an instance of a class registered via
	QJS_NewClass().  Retrieve the pointer later with
	QJS_GetOpaque() or QJS_GetOpaque2().

    INPUTS
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object value.
	opaque	- Arbitrary C pointer, or NULL.

    RESULT
	None.

    NOTES
	Note the register assignment: the object pointer is in A1,
	the opaque pointer is in A0.  The function takes the
	arguments in reverse of the C signature order.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetOpaque, QJS_GetOpaque2, QJS_NewClass


quickjs.library/QJS_GetOpaque                       quickjs.library/QJS_GetOpaque

    NAME
	QJS_GetOpaque -- Retrieve the class-opaque pointer without
	    type checking.

    SYNOPSIS
	ptr = QJS_GetOpaque(obj_ptr, class_id)
	D0                  A0       D0

	APTR QJS_GetOpaque(const JSValue *obj_ptr,
			   JSClassID class_id);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the opaque pointer set via QJS_SetOpaque() if the
	object IS an instance of the given class; NULL otherwise
	(including when the object does not match the class).

	No exception is thrown; prefer QJS_GetOpaque2() when you
	want an automatic TypeError on mismatch.

    INPUTS
	obj_ptr  - Pointer to the object.
	class_id - Expected class ID.

    RESULT
	ptr - Opaque pointer, or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetOpaque2, QJS_SetOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_GetOpaque2                     quickjs.library/QJS_GetOpaque2

    NAME
	QJS_GetOpaque2 -- Retrieve the class-opaque pointer with
	    type checking.

    SYNOPSIS
	ptr = QJS_GetOpaque2(ctx, obj_ptr, class_id)
	D0                   A0   A1       D0

	APTR QJS_GetOpaque2(JSContext *ctx,
			    const JSValue *obj_ptr,
			    JSClassID class_id);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_GetOpaque() but if the object is NOT an instance
	of the expected class, throws a TypeError into the context
	and returns NULL.  Canonical check at the top of C methods
	on native classes.

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	obj_ptr  - Pointer to the object (typically `this_val`).
	class_id - Expected class ID.

    RESULT
	ptr - Opaque pointer, or NULL (with exception pending).

    EXAMPLE
	static JSValue my_method(JSContext *ctx, JSValueConst this_v,
				 int argc, JSValueConst *argv) {
	    MyData *s = QJS_GetOpaque2(ctx, &this_v, my_class_id);
	    if (!s) return JS_EXCEPTION;
	    /* use s... */
	}

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetOpaque, QJS_SetOpaque


quickjs.library/QJS_GetOwnPropertyNames     QJS_GetOwnPropertyNames

    NAME
	QJS_GetOwnPropertyNames -- Enumerate an object's own
	    property keys.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_GetOwnPropertyNames(ctx, ptab, plen, obj_ptr, flags)
	D0                           A0   A1    A2    A3       D0

	LONG QJS_GetOwnPropertyNames(JSContext *ctx,
				     JSPropertyEnum **ptab,
				     ULONG *plen,
				     const JSValue *obj_ptr,
				     ULONG flags);

    FUNCTION
	Allocates an array of JSPropertyEnum structures, one per
	own property of the object, and returns it through *ptab
	plus *plen.  The `flags` control what is included:

	    JS_GPN_STRING_MASK     -- string keys
	    JS_GPN_SYMBOL_MASK     -- symbol keys
	    JS_GPN_PRIVATE_MASK    -- private fields
	    JS_GPN_ENUM_ONLY       -- enumerable only
	    JS_GPN_SET_ENUM        -- mark the enum field

	The caller must release the array with
	QJS_FreePropertyEnum() when done.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	ptab	- Output pointer for the allocated array.
	plen	- Output pointer for the count.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the object.
	flags	- JS_GPN_* mask.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreePropertyEnum, QJS_GetProperty


quickjs.library/QJS_FreePropertyEnum       quickjs.library/QJS_FreePropertyEnum

    NAME
	QJS_FreePropertyEnum -- Release an array returned by
	    QJS_GetOwnPropertyNames().

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_FreePropertyEnum(ctx, tab, len)
			     A0   A1   D0

	VOID QJS_FreePropertyEnum(JSContext *ctx,
				  JSPropertyEnum *tab, ULONG len);

    FUNCTION
	Frees every atom in the enumeration and the array itself.
	Must be called with the same ctx that produced the enum.

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.
	tab - Array previously returned through *ptab.
	len - Count previously returned through *plen.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetOwnPropertyNames


quickjs.library/QJS_Call                               quickjs.library/QJS_Call

    NAME
	QJS_Call -- Call a JavaScript function.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_Call(result, ctx, func_ptr, this_ptr, argc, argv_addr)
		 A0      A1   A2        A3        D0    D1

	VOID QJS_Call(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
		      const JSValue *func_ptr,
		      const JSValue *this_ptr,
		      int argc, const JSValue *argv_addr);

    FUNCTION
	Calls the function `*func_ptr` with `*this_ptr` as the
	`this` binding and `argc` arguments from the `argv_addr`
	array.  Stores the return value (or an exception) in
	*result.

	The argv_addr array holds JSValues (not pointers), packed
	consecutively.  QJS_Call() reads them in place; the values
	remain the caller's property.

    INPUTS
	result	  - Output JSValue (return value or exception).
	ctx	  - Host context.
	func_ptr  - Pointer to the function to call.
	this_ptr  - Pointer to the `this` binding.  Pass a pointer
		    to JS_UNDEFINED for no `this`.
	argc	  - Number of arguments.
	argv_addr - Pointer to the first of `argc` contiguous
		    JSValues, or NULL if argc is 0.

    RESULT
	None.  On exception *result has its IS_EXCEPTION flag set.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue args[2], ret;
	QJS_NewNumber(&args[0], ctx, &(double){1.0});
	QJS_NewNumber(&args[1], ctx, &(double){2.0});
	QJS_Call(&ret, ctx, &sum_fn, &global, 2, args);
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &args[0]);
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &args[1]);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Invoke, QJS_CallConstructor, QJS_NewCFunction2


quickjs.library/QJS_Invoke                           quickjs.library/QJS_Invoke

    NAME
	QJS_Invoke -- Call a method on an object by atom.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_Invoke(result, ctx, this_ptr, argv, atom, argc)
		   A0      A1   A2        A3    D0    D1

	VOID QJS_Invoke(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			const JSValue *this_ptr,
			const JSValue *argv,
			JSAtom atom, int argc);

    FUNCTION
	Convenience wrapper that looks up the method `atom` on
	`*this_ptr`, then calls it with `*this_ptr` as receiver
	and `argc` arguments from `argv`.  Equivalent to the JS
	expression `this[method](...args)`.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	this_ptr - Pointer to the object holding the method.
	argv	 - Pointer to argument array.
	atom	 - Method name as a JSAtom.
	argc	 - Number of arguments.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSAtom slice = QJS_NewAtom(ctx, "slice");
	JSValue args[2], result;
	QJS_NewNumber(&args[0], ctx, &(double){0});
	QJS_NewNumber(&args[1], ctx, &(double){5});
	QJS_Invoke(&result, ctx, &str, args, slice, 2);
	QJS_FreeAtom(ctx, slice);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Call, QJS_GetProperty


quickjs.library/QJS_CallConstructor           quickjs.library/QJS_CallConstructor

    NAME
	QJS_CallConstructor -- Call a constructor with `new`.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_CallConstructor(result, ctx, func_ptr, argv, argc)
			    A0      A1   A2        A3    D0

	VOID QJS_CallConstructor(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				 const JSValue *func_ptr,
				 const JSValue *argv, int argc);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to the JS expression `new func(...args)`.
	The function must have a [[Construct]] slot (see
	QJS_IsConstructor).

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue for the new instance.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	func_ptr - Pointer to the constructor.
	argv	 - Pointer to argument array.
	argc	 - Number of arguments.

    RESULT
	None.  *result holds the new instance or an exception.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue args[1], instance;
	QJS_NewStringLen(&args[0], ctx, "hello", 5);
	QJS_CallConstructor(&instance, ctx, &String_ctor, args, 1);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Call, QJS_IsConstructor


quickjs.library/QJS_NewCFunction2               quickjs.library/QJS_NewCFunction2

    NAME
	QJS_NewCFunction2 -- Register a C function as a JS value.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewCFunction2(result, ctx, func, name, length, cproto,
			  magic)
	                  A0      A1   A2    A3    D0      D1
			  D2

	VOID QJS_NewCFunction2(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			       JSCFunction *func, CONST_STRPTR name,
			       int length, JSCFunctionEnum cproto,
			       int magic);

    FUNCTION
	Wraps a native C function pointer as a JavaScript
	function.  The `cproto` selects the signature expected by
	the C function:

	    JS_CFUNC_generic     - int argc, JSValueConst *argv
	    JS_CFUNC_constructor - same, but callable with `new`
	    JS_CFUNC_getter      - no args
	    JS_CFUNC_setter      - one arg
	    JS_CFUNC_f_f         - one double -> double
	    JS_CFUNC_f_f_f       - two doubles -> double
	    ... (see <quickjs.h>)

	The `magic` field is an integer passed to the C function,
	letting several JS names share a single C implementation
	that switches on magic.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue.
	ctx	- Host context.
	func	- C function pointer.
	name	- Name used by Function.prototype.name and
		  stack traces.
	length	- Number reported by the function's .length
		  property.
	cproto	- Signature enum.
	magic	- User-supplied integer.

    RESULT
	None.  *result is the callable function value.

    EXAMPLE
	static JSValue js_my_fn(JSContext *ctx, JSValueConst this_v,
				int argc, JSValueConst *argv) {
	    return JS_NewInt32(ctx, 42);
	}
	JSValue fn;
	QJS_NewCFunction2(&fn, ctx, js_my_fn, "answer", 0,
			  JS_CFUNC_generic, 0);
	QJS_SetPropertyStr(ctx, &global, "answer", &fn);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Call, QJS_SetConstructor, QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList


quickjs.library/QJS_NewClassID                     quickjs.library/QJS_NewClassID

    NAME
	QJS_NewClassID -- Allocate a fresh class ID.

    SYNOPSIS
	id = QJS_NewClassID(rt, pclass_id)
	D0                  A0  A1

	JSClassID QJS_NewClassID(JSRuntime *rt, JSClassID *pclass_id);

    FUNCTION
	Allocates a new, unused JSClassID within the runtime.  If
	*pclass_id is already non-zero on entry, the existing ID is
	returned unchanged; otherwise a new ID is assigned and
	stored in *pclass_id and returned.

	This idempotent behaviour lets you safely call it during
	module init from multiple contexts -- the first call does
	the allocation, later calls are no-ops.

    INPUTS
	rt	  - The runtime.
	pclass_id - Pointer to storage for the class ID.  Typically
		    a static file-scope variable initialized to zero.

    RESULT
	id - The class ID (also stored in *pclass_id).

    EXAMPLE
	static JSClassID my_class_id;
	QJS_NewClassID(rt, &my_class_id);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewClass, QJS_IsRegisteredClass


quickjs.library/QJS_NewClass                         quickjs.library/QJS_NewClass

    NAME
	QJS_NewClass -- Register a native class with the runtime.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_NewClass(rt, class_def, class_id)
	D0                A0  A1         D0

	LONG QJS_NewClass(JSRuntime *rt, const JSClassDef *class_def,
			  JSClassID class_id);

    FUNCTION
	Installs a JSClassDef (name, finalizer, GC-mark callback,
	call hook, exotic-behaviour table) under the given
	`class_id`.  Afterwards, QJS_NewObjectClass() can create
	instances of the class.

	Must be called once per runtime, typically during the
	module init function.

    INPUTS
	rt	  - The runtime.
	class_def - Pointer to a JSClassDef (must remain valid for
		    the life of the runtime -- pass a static const).
	class_id  - The ID allocated by QJS_NewClassID().

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on failure.

    EXAMPLE
	static const JSClassDef my_class_def = {
	    "MyWidget",
	    js_my_widget_finalizer,
	    NULL, NULL, NULL,
	};
	QJS_NewClassID(rt, &my_class_id);
	QJS_NewClass(rt, &my_class_def, my_class_id);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewClassID, QJS_SetClassProto, QJS_NewObjectClass


quickjs.library/QJS_IsRegisteredClass         quickjs.library/QJS_IsRegisteredClass

    NAME
	QJS_IsRegisteredClass -- Check whether a class ID is in use.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsRegisteredClass(rt, class_id)
	D0                             A0  D0

	BOOL QJS_IsRegisteredClass(JSRuntime *rt, JSClassID class_id);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if the class ID has been registered with
	QJS_NewClass() in this runtime, FALSE otherwise.

    INPUTS
	rt	 - The runtime.
	class_id - The class ID to test.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewClass, QJS_GetClassID


quickjs.library/QJS_GetClassID                     quickjs.library/QJS_GetClassID

    NAME
	QJS_GetClassID -- Return the class ID of an object.

    SYNOPSIS
	id = QJS_GetClassID(val_ptr)
	D0                  A0

	JSClassID QJS_GetClassID(const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the JSClassID of the object pointed to by
	`val_ptr`, or JS_CLASS_OBJECT for plain objects,
	or 0 for non-objects.

    INPUTS
	val_ptr - Pointer to a value.

    RESULT
	id - The class ID.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewObjectClass, QJS_GetOpaque2


quickjs.library/QJS_SetClassProto                 quickjs.library/QJS_SetClassProto

    NAME
	QJS_SetClassProto -- Install the prototype object for a
	    native class.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetClassProto(ctx, class_id, obj_ptr)
			  A0   D0        A2

	VOID QJS_SetClassProto(JSContext *ctx, JSClassID class_id,
			       const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Sets the prototype used by QJS_NewObjectClass() when
	creating instances of `class_id`.  Normally called once per
	context during module init, after QJS_NewClass().

	Takes ownership of *obj_ptr.

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	class_id - The class.
	obj_ptr  - Pointer to the prototype object (typically
		   created with QJS_NewObject() then populated via
		   QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList()).

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetClassProto, QJS_NewClass, QJS_NewObjectClass,
	QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList


quickjs.library/QJS_GetClassProto                 quickjs.library/QJS_GetClassProto

    NAME
	QJS_GetClassProto -- Retrieve the prototype for a native
	    class.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetClassProto(result, ctx, class_id)
			  A0      A1   D0

	VOID QJS_GetClassProto(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			       JSClassID class_id);

    FUNCTION
	Returns (with an added reference) the prototype previously
	installed with QJS_SetClassProto().  Returns JS_NULL if no
	prototype was set.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	class_id - The class.

    RESULT
	None.  Release *result with QJS_FreeValue() when done.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetClassProto, QJS_NewObjectClass


quickjs.library/QJS_GetFunctionProto             quickjs.library/QJS_GetFunctionProto

    NAME
	QJS_GetFunctionProto -- Return Function.prototype.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetFunctionProto(result, ctx)
			     A0      A1

	VOID QJS_GetFunctionProto(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Returns (with an added reference) the context's
	Function.prototype object.  Useful when constructing
	native callables whose prototype chain must match
	JS-defined functions.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.

    RESULT
	None.  Release with QJS_FreeValue().

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewCFunction2


quickjs.library/QJS_SetConstructor               quickjs.library/QJS_SetConstructor

    NAME
	QJS_SetConstructor -- Pair a constructor function with its
	    prototype.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetConstructor(ctx, func_ptr, proto_ptr)
			   A0   A1        A2

	VOID QJS_SetConstructor(JSContext *ctx,
				const JSValue *func_ptr,
				const JSValue *proto_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Sets `func.prototype = proto` and `proto.constructor =
	func`, wiring up the standard constructor/prototype
	relationship.  Called during class setup after creating
	the constructor with QJS_NewCFunction2(JS_CFUNC_constructor).

    INPUTS
	ctx	  - Host context.
	func_ptr  - Pointer to the constructor function.
	proto_ptr - Pointer to the prototype object.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue proto, ctor;
	QJS_NewObject(&proto, ctx);
	QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList(ctx, &proto, proto_funcs, n);
	QJS_NewCFunction2(&ctor, ctx, my_ctor, "My", 1,
			  JS_CFUNC_constructor, 0);
	QJS_SetConstructor(ctx, &ctor, &proto);
	QJS_SetClassProto(ctx, my_class_id, &proto);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewCFunction2, QJS_SetClassProto,
	QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList


quickjs.library/QJS_SetConstructorBit         quickjs.library/QJS_SetConstructorBit

    NAME
	QJS_SetConstructorBit -- Flip the [[Construct]] bit on a
	    function.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SetConstructorBit(ctx, func_ptr, val)
	D0                         A0   A1        D0

	LONG QJS_SetConstructorBit(JSContext *ctx,
				   const JSValue *func_ptr, BOOL val);

    FUNCTION
	Marks or unmarks a function as a constructor.  Rarely
	needed: normally constructors are created as such via
	QJS_NewCFunction2(..., JS_CFUNC_constructor, ...).

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	func_ptr - Pointer to the function.
	val	 - TRUE to make constructable, FALSE otherwise.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 on success, 0 on failure.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewCFunction2, QJS_IsConstructor


quickjs.library/QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList

    NAME
	QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList -- Bulk-install methods/accessors
	    on an object.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList(ctx, obj_ptr, tab, len)
				    A0   A1       A2   D0

	VOID QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList(JSContext *ctx,
					const JSValue *obj_ptr,
					const JSCFunctionListEntry *tab,
					int len);

    FUNCTION
	Installs an array of JSCFunctionListEntry structures as
	properties of the object.  Each entry can describe a
	method, getter/setter, constant, or string property.

	This is the primary way to populate a class prototype with
	many methods at once.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the target object (usually a prototype).
	tab	- Pointer to the entry array (must remain valid
		  during the call; typically static const).
	len	- Number of entries.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	static const JSCFunctionListEntry my_proto_funcs[] = {
	    JS_CFUNC_DEF("getName", 0, js_get_name),
	    JS_CFUNC_DEF("setName", 1, js_set_name),
	    JS_CGETSET_DEF("age", js_get_age, js_set_age),
	};
	QJS_SetPropertyFunctionList(ctx, &proto, my_proto_funcs,
	    sizeof(my_proto_funcs) / sizeof(my_proto_funcs[0]));

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetPropertyStr, QJS_NewCFunction2


quickjs.library/QJS_Throw                             quickjs.library/QJS_Throw

    NAME
	QJS_Throw -- Install a value as the current exception.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_Throw(result, ctx, obj_ptr)
		  A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_Throw(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
		       const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Stores the value `*obj_ptr` as the active exception for
	the context and sets *result to the "exception indicator"
	JSValue, which you return up the call stack.  Takes
	ownership of the reference in *obj_ptr.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue (the exception indicator).
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the value to throw.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	/* In a C native method, on error: */
	JSValue err, indicator;
	QJS_NewError(&err, ctx);
	QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr(ctx, &err,
	    &(JSValue){JS_NewString(ctx, "bad arg")},
	    "message", JS_PROP_WRITABLE | JS_PROP_CONFIGURABLE);
	QJS_Throw(&indicator, ctx, &err);
	return indicator;

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetException, QJS_NewError, QJS_HasException


quickjs.library/QJS_GetException                 quickjs.library/QJS_GetException

    NAME
	QJS_GetException -- Retrieve and clear the pending exception.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetException(result, ctx)
			 A0      A1

	VOID QJS_GetException(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Stores the active exception in *result and clears it from
	the context, so subsequent code no longer sees one pending.
	If no exception is pending, *result is JS_UNDEFINED.

	The caller owns the returned reference and must release it
	with QJS_FreeValue().

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	if (QJS_IsException(&v)) {
	    JSValue ex;
	    QJS_GetException(&ex, ctx);
	    const char *s = QJS_ToCStringLen2(ctx, NULL, &ex, FALSE);
	    fprintf(stderr, "error: %s\n", s ? s : "(unknown)");
	    if (s) QJS_FreeCString(ctx, s);
	    QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &ex);
	}

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_HasException, QJS_Throw


quickjs.library/QJS_HasException                 quickjs.library/QJS_HasException

    NAME
	QJS_HasException -- Test whether an exception is pending.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_HasException(ctx)
	D0                        A0

	BOOL QJS_HasException(JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if an exception is currently pending on the
	context, FALSE otherwise.  Does NOT consume the exception.

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetException, QJS_Throw


quickjs.library/QJS_NewError                         quickjs.library/QJS_NewError

    NAME
	QJS_NewError -- Create a new Error object.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewError(result, ctx)
		     A0      A1

	VOID QJS_NewError(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a plain Error object.  Populate its .message
	property via QJS_DefinePropertyValueStr() or
	QJS_SetPropertyStr() before throwing.

	For typed errors (TypeError, RangeError, etc.) the
	library does not expose dedicated constructors because
	the upstream JS_ThrowTypeError variants are variadic
	and cannot cross the library boundary.  Use:

	    JSValue err;
	    QJS_Eval(&err, ctx, "new TypeError(msg)", ..., 0);

	or build an Error and set .name yourself.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_Throw, QJS_ThrowOutOfMemory


quickjs.library/QJS_ThrowOutOfMemory           quickjs.library/QJS_ThrowOutOfMemory

    NAME
	QJS_ThrowOutOfMemory -- Signal an OOM condition.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_ThrowOutOfMemory(result, ctx)
			     A0      A1

	VOID QJS_ThrowOutOfMemory(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx);

    FUNCTION
	Installs the engine's canonical "out of memory" error as
	the pending exception and returns an exception indicator
	in *result.  Intended for allocation-failure paths in
	native code.

	Does not allocate (unlike a generic QJS_NewError() +
	QJS_Throw() sequence), so it is safe to call when the
	heap is truly exhausted.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue (exception indicator).
	ctx    - Host context.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	void *p = malloc(size);
	if (!p) {
	    JSValue ex;
	    QJS_ThrowOutOfMemory(&ex, ctx);
	    return ex;
	}

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewError, QJS_Throw


quickjs.library/QJS_NewAtom                           quickjs.library/QJS_NewAtom

    NAME
	QJS_NewAtom -- Intern a C string into an atom.

    SYNOPSIS
	atom = QJS_NewAtom(ctx, str)
	D0                 A0   A1

	JSAtom QJS_NewAtom(JSContext *ctx, CONST_STRPTR str);

    FUNCTION
	Returns an interned atom representing the given
	NUL-terminated UTF-8 string.  Atoms are 32-bit handles
	used for fast property-key comparisons; identical strings
	always produce the same atom within a runtime.

	Every atom returned must eventually be released with
	QJS_FreeAtom() or atoms will leak.

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.
	str - NUL-terminated string.

    RESULT
	atom - New atom (or existing if the string was already
	       interned).  JS_ATOM_NULL on OOM.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewAtomLen, QJS_FreeAtom, QJS_AtomToString


quickjs.library/QJS_NewAtomLen                     quickjs.library/QJS_NewAtomLen

    NAME
	QJS_NewAtomLen -- Intern a byte buffer into an atom.

    SYNOPSIS
	atom = QJS_NewAtomLen(ctx, str, len)
	D0                    A0   A1   D0

	JSAtom QJS_NewAtomLen(JSContext *ctx, CONST_STRPTR str,
			      ULONG len);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_NewAtom() but for strings that are not
	NUL-terminated or may contain embedded NULs.

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.
	str - Pointer to the bytes.
	len - Number of bytes.

    RESULT
	atom - New atom.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewAtom


quickjs.library/QJS_NewAtomUInt32               quickjs.library/QJS_NewAtomUInt32

    NAME
	QJS_NewAtomUInt32 -- Create an atom from an integer index.

    SYNOPSIS
	atom = QJS_NewAtomUInt32(ctx, n)
	D0                       A0   D0

	JSAtom QJS_NewAtomUInt32(JSContext *ctx, ULONG n);

    FUNCTION
	Creates an atom whose string form is the decimal
	representation of `n`.  Equivalent to QJS_NewAtomLen()
	with a formatted buffer, but faster and always
	canonical.

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.
	n   - Unsigned 32-bit index.

    RESULT
	atom - New atom.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewAtom, QJS_ValueToAtom


quickjs.library/QJS_DupAtom                           quickjs.library/QJS_DupAtom

    NAME
	QJS_DupAtom -- Add one reference to an atom.

    SYNOPSIS
	atom2 = QJS_DupAtom(ctx, v)
	D0                  A0   D0

	JSAtom QJS_DupAtom(JSContext *ctx, JSAtom v);

    FUNCTION
	Increments the atom's reference count and returns the
	same atom value.  Used when storing an atom in a long-
	lived structure while the original owner also keeps it.

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.
	v   - The atom.

    RESULT
	atom2 - Same atom value as `v`.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewAtom, QJS_FreeAtom


quickjs.library/QJS_FreeAtom                         quickjs.library/QJS_FreeAtom

    NAME
	QJS_FreeAtom -- Release one reference to an atom.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_FreeAtom(ctx, v)
		     A0   D0

	VOID QJS_FreeAtom(JSContext *ctx, JSAtom v);

    FUNCTION
	Decrements the atom's reference count.  The underlying
	string is freed when the count hits zero.

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.
	v   - The atom.

    RESULT
	None.

    NOTES
	Calling with JS_ATOM_NULL is a safe no-op.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewAtom, QJS_DupAtom


quickjs.library/QJS_AtomToValue                   quickjs.library/QJS_AtomToValue

    NAME
	QJS_AtomToValue -- Convert an atom to its string JSValue
	    form (or Symbol).

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_AtomToValue(result, ctx, atom)
			A0      A1   D0

	VOID QJS_AtomToValue(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			     JSAtom atom);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the JSValue whose atom-form is `atom`.  For
	string atoms this yields a JS string; for symbol atoms,
	the Symbol itself.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	atom   - The atom.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AtomToString, QJS_ValueToAtom


quickjs.library/QJS_AtomToString                 quickjs.library/QJS_AtomToString

    NAME
	QJS_AtomToString -- Convert an atom to a string JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_AtomToString(result, ctx, atom)
			 A0      A1   D0

	VOID QJS_AtomToString(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			      JSAtom atom);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_AtomToValue() but always returns a string,
	converting Symbols via their description.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue (a string).
	ctx    - Host context.
	atom   - The atom.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AtomToValue, QJS_AtomToCStringLen


quickjs.library/QJS_AtomToCStringLen         quickjs.library/QJS_AtomToCStringLen

    NAME
	QJS_AtomToCStringLen -- Obtain a C-string view of an atom.

    SYNOPSIS
	str = QJS_AtomToCStringLen(ctx, plen, atom)
	D0                         A0   A1    D0

	CONST_STRPTR QJS_AtomToCStringLen(JSContext *ctx,
					  size_t *plen, JSAtom atom);

    FUNCTION
	Returns a pointer to engine-owned UTF-8 bytes representing
	the atom's string form.  If `plen` is non-NULL, *plen
	receives the byte length.

	Release the pointer with QJS_FreeCString() when done.

    INPUTS
	ctx  - Host context.
	plen - Optional output for length, or NULL.
	atom - The atom.

    RESULT
	str - Pointer to bytes, or NULL on error.  Caller must
	      free via QJS_FreeCString().

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreeCString, QJS_AtomToString


quickjs.library/QJS_ValueToAtom                   quickjs.library/QJS_ValueToAtom

    NAME
	QJS_ValueToAtom -- Intern a JSValue as an atom.

    SYNOPSIS
	atom = QJS_ValueToAtom(ctx, val_ptr)
	D0                     A0   A1

	JSAtom QJS_ValueToAtom(JSContext *ctx,
			       const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Converts *val_ptr to a property key (via ToPropertyKey)
	and returns the corresponding atom.  Both strings and
	Symbols are supported.

	The returned atom carries a reference; release with
	QJS_FreeAtom().

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	val_ptr - Pointer to the source value.

    RESULT
	atom - New atom, or JS_ATOM_NULL on error.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_FreeAtom, QJS_AtomToValue


quickjs.library/QJS_ParseJSON                       quickjs.library/QJS_ParseJSON

    NAME
	QJS_ParseJSON -- Parse a JSON document into a JSValue.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_ParseJSON(result, ctx, buf, filename, buf_len)
		      A0      A1   A2   A3        D0

	VOID QJS_ParseJSON(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			   CONST_STRPTR buf, CONST_STRPTR filename,
			   ULONG buf_len);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to `JSON.parse(buf)` called from JavaScript.
	On syntax errors, *result is an exception value whose
	message identifies the problem; `filename` is included in
	stack traces.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue.
	ctx	 - Host context.
	buf	 - JSON source bytes.
	filename - Name shown in error messages.
	buf_len  - Length of buf in bytes.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue parsed;
	const char *text = "{\"x\":1,\"y\":2}";
	QJS_ParseJSON(&parsed, ctx, text, "<in>", strlen(text));

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_JSONStringify


quickjs.library/QJS_JSONStringify             quickjs.library/QJS_JSONStringify

    NAME
	QJS_JSONStringify -- Serialize a JSValue to JSON text.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_JSONStringify(result, ctx, obj_ptr)
			  A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_JSONStringify(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			       const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Equivalent to `JSON.stringify(obj)`.  Returns a string
	JSValue; convert to C string with QJS_ToCStringLen2().

	Note: the upstream JS_JSONStringify() supports replacer
	and indent arguments; the library exposes only the
	common no-args form.  For custom formatting, use
	QJS_Eval() to run JS code that calls JSON.stringify
	directly.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue (a string).
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the value to serialize.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ParseJSON, QJS_ToCStringLen2


quickjs.library/QJS_WriteObject                   quickjs.library/QJS_WriteObject

    NAME
	QJS_WriteObject -- Serialize a value to QuickJS binary
	    format.

    SYNOPSIS
	buf = QJS_WriteObject(ctx, psize, obj_ptr, flags)
	D0                    A0   A1     A2       D0

	APTR QJS_WriteObject(JSContext *ctx, size_t *psize,
			     const JSValue *obj_ptr, ULONG flags);

    FUNCTION
	Produces a binary representation of the value suitable
	for later QJS_ReadObject().  The format handles objects,
	arrays, strings, numbers, TypedArrays, and compiled
	functions (for bytecode caching).

	The returned buffer is allocated with QJS_Malloc(); caller
	must free with QJS_Free().

	Flags:
	    JS_WRITE_OBJ_BYTECODE -- allow compiled functions
	    JS_WRITE_OBJ_REFERENCE -- allow object references
	    JS_WRITE_OBJ_SAB	  -- allow SharedArrayBuffer
	    JS_WRITE_OBJ_STRIP_SOURCE -- drop source text

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	psize	- Output for the buffer length.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the value to serialize.
	flags	- JS_WRITE_OBJ_* mask.

    RESULT
	buf - Newly-allocated byte buffer (caller frees via
	      QJS_Free()), or NULL on error.  *psize receives the
	      length.

    EXAMPLE
	/* Compile once, run many times: */
	JSValue fn;
	QJS_Eval(&fn, ctx, src, len, "<in>", JS_EVAL_FLAG_COMPILE_ONLY);
	size_t sz;
	UBYTE *blob = QJS_WriteObject(ctx, &sz, &fn,
				      JS_WRITE_OBJ_BYTECODE);
	/* ... save blob to disk ... */
	QJS_Free(ctx, blob);
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &fn);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ReadObject, QJS_EvalFunction


quickjs.library/QJS_ReadObject                     quickjs.library/QJS_ReadObject

    NAME
	QJS_ReadObject -- Deserialize a value from QuickJS binary
	    format.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_ReadObject(result, ctx, buf, buf_len, flags)
		       A0      A1   A2   D0       D1

	VOID QJS_ReadObject(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			    const UBYTE *buf, ULONG buf_len,
			    ULONG flags);

    FUNCTION
	Reads a buffer produced by QJS_WriteObject() and
	reconstructs the original value.  Flags must match those
	used at write time.

    INPUTS
	result	- Output JSValue.
	ctx	- Host context.
	buf	- Input buffer.
	buf_len - Input length.
	flags	- JS_READ_OBJ_* mask (same semantics as
		  JS_WRITE_OBJ_* above).

    RESULT
	None.  On failure *result is an exception.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_WriteObject, QJS_EvalFunction


quickjs.library/QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy       QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy

    NAME
	QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy -- Create an ArrayBuffer from a
	    copy of host memory.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy(result, ctx, buf, len)
			       A0      A1   A2   D0

	VOID QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				    const UBYTE *buf, ULONG len);

    FUNCTION
	Allocates a fresh ArrayBuffer of `len` bytes, copies the
	contents of `buf` into it, and stores the resulting
	JSValue in *result.  The copy is owned by the engine;
	after this call the caller can reuse or free `buf`.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	buf    - Source bytes (may be NULL if len is 0).
	len    - Number of bytes to copy.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	UBYTE header[16];
	Read(fh, header, 16);
	JSValue ab;
	QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy(&ab, ctx, header, 16);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetArrayBuffer, QJS_NewUint8ArrayCopy


quickjs.library/QJS_GetArrayBuffer             quickjs.library/QJS_GetArrayBuffer

    NAME
	QJS_GetArrayBuffer -- Get a pointer to an ArrayBuffer's
	    data.

    SYNOPSIS
	buf = QJS_GetArrayBuffer(ctx, psize, obj_ptr)
	D0                       A0   A1     A2

	UBYTE *QJS_GetArrayBuffer(JSContext *ctx, size_t *psize,
				  const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	If *obj_ptr is an ArrayBuffer, returns a pointer to its
	internal byte storage and stores the byte length in
	*psize.  Returns NULL and sets an exception otherwise.

	The returned pointer is valid until the ArrayBuffer is
	detached or garbage-collected.  Do NOT free it.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	psize	- Output for buffer length, or NULL to skip.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the ArrayBuffer.

    RESULT
	buf - Pointer to internal bytes, or NULL on error.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy, QJS_DetachArrayBuffer,
	QJS_GetUint8Array


quickjs.library/QJS_DetachArrayBuffer         QJS_DetachArrayBuffer

    NAME
	QJS_DetachArrayBuffer -- Detach an ArrayBuffer's storage.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_DetachArrayBuffer(ctx, obj_ptr)
			      A0   A1

	VOID QJS_DetachArrayBuffer(JSContext *ctx,
				   const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Releases the ArrayBuffer's backing memory and marks the
	buffer detached.  Any further access through the buffer
	or typed-array views on it throws TypeError.

	Used when the host needs to reclaim the memory before
	the GC would run.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the ArrayBuffer.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetArrayBuffer


quickjs.library/QJS_GetUint8Array               quickjs.library/QJS_GetUint8Array

    NAME
	QJS_GetUint8Array -- Access a Uint8Array as host bytes.

    SYNOPSIS
	buf = QJS_GetUint8Array(ctx, psize, obj_ptr)
	D0                      A0   A1     A2

	UBYTE *QJS_GetUint8Array(JSContext *ctx, size_t *psize,
				 const JSValue *obj_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Like QJS_GetArrayBuffer() but accepts a Uint8Array view
	and returns a pointer to its visible bytes (accounting
	for byteOffset and byteLength).  Useful when JS code
	passes binary data as Uint8Array rather than ArrayBuffer.

    INPUTS
	ctx	- Host context.
	psize	- Output for visible length.
	obj_ptr - Pointer to the Uint8Array.

    RESULT
	buf - Pointer to bytes, or NULL on error.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewUint8ArrayCopy, QJS_GetArrayBuffer


quickjs.library/QJS_NewUint8ArrayCopy       QJS_NewUint8ArrayCopy

    NAME
	QJS_NewUint8ArrayCopy -- Create a Uint8Array from a copy
	    of host memory.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewUint8ArrayCopy(result, ctx, buf, len)
			      A0      A1   A2   D0

	VOID QJS_NewUint8ArrayCopy(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				   const UBYTE *buf, ULONG len);

    FUNCTION
	Allocates a Uint8Array of `len` bytes backed by a fresh
	ArrayBuffer, copies `buf` into it.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	buf    - Source bytes.
	len    - Number of bytes.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_GetUint8Array, QJS_NewArrayBufferCopy


quickjs.library/QJS_NewPromiseCapability     QJS_NewPromiseCapability

    NAME
	QJS_NewPromiseCapability -- Create a new Promise plus its
	    resolve/reject callbacks.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_NewPromiseCapability(result, ctx, resolving_funcs)
				 A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_NewPromiseCapability(JSValue *result,
				      JSContext *ctx,
				      JSValue *resolving_funcs);

    FUNCTION
	Creates a new pending Promise and two JSValue callbacks --
	its resolve function at resolving_funcs[0] and reject
	function at resolving_funcs[1].  Call one of the callbacks
	via QJS_Call() to settle the promise.

	The caller is responsible for:
	    * releasing both resolving_funcs[] values with
	      QJS_FreeValue() after settling the promise or
	      storing them durably;
	    * releasing the returned *result with QJS_FreeValue()
	      when handing it back to JS code.

    INPUTS
	result		- Output JSValue (the new Promise).
	ctx		- Host context.
	resolving_funcs - Caller-provided array of 2 JSValues
			  to receive the resolve/reject callbacks.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue resolving[2], promise;
	QJS_NewPromiseCapability(&promise, ctx, resolving);
	/* later, when we have the result: */
	QJS_Call(&ret, ctx, &resolving[0], &(JSValue){JS_UNDEFINED},
		 1, &final_value);
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &resolving[0]);
	QJS_FreeValue(ctx, &resolving[1]);
	return promise;

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_PromiseState, QJS_PromiseResult, QJS_IsPromise


quickjs.library/QJS_PromiseState                 quickjs.library/QJS_PromiseState

    NAME
	QJS_PromiseState -- Query a promise's current state.

    SYNOPSIS
	state = QJS_PromiseState(ctx, promise_ptr)
	D0                       A0   A1

	JSPromiseStateEnum QJS_PromiseState(JSContext *ctx,
					    const JSValue *promise_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Returns one of:

	    JS_PROMISE_PENDING    (0) - not yet settled
	    JS_PROMISE_FULFILLED  (1) - resolved successfully
	    JS_PROMISE_REJECTED   (2) - rejected

	Returns -1 if *promise_ptr is not a promise.

    INPUTS
	ctx	    - Host context.
	promise_ptr - Pointer to the promise.

    RESULT
	state - Promise state enum, or -1.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_PromiseResult, QJS_IsPromise


quickjs.library/QJS_PromiseResult               quickjs.library/QJS_PromiseResult

    NAME
	QJS_PromiseResult -- Retrieve a settled promise's value
	    or rejection reason.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_PromiseResult(result, ctx, promise_ptr)
			  A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_PromiseResult(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			       const JSValue *promise_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	For a fulfilled promise, stores the resolved value in
	*result.  For a rejected promise, stores the rejection
	reason.  Behaviour is undefined for pending promises --
	check QJS_PromiseState() first.

    INPUTS
	result	    - Output JSValue.
	ctx	    - Host context.
	promise_ptr - Pointer to the settled promise.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_PromiseState, QJS_NewPromiseCapability


quickjs.library/QJS_SetInterruptHandler     QJS_SetInterruptHandler

    NAME
	QJS_SetInterruptHandler -- Register a callback invoked
	    periodically during script execution.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetInterruptHandler(rt, cb, opaque)
				A0  A1  A2

	VOID QJS_SetInterruptHandler(JSRuntime *rt,
				     JSInterruptHandler *cb,
				     APTR opaque);

    FUNCTION
	The engine calls `cb(rt, opaque)` at safe points during
	evaluation.  If the callback returns non-zero, the engine
	throws a "interrupted" exception and unwinds the current
	call.

	Typical use: watchdog timer, Ctrl-C detection, or quota
	enforcement.

    INPUTS
	rt     - The runtime.
	cb     - Callback (VOID (*)(JSRuntime *, APTR) returning
		 LONG), or NULL to disable.
	opaque - User pointer passed to the callback.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	static int check_ctrl_c(JSRuntime *rt, void *op) {
	    return (SetSignal(0, 0) & SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C) ? 1 : 0;
	}
	QJS_SetInterruptHandler(rt, check_ctrl_c, NULL);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_RunGC


quickjs.library/QJS_SetHostPromiseRejectionTracker QJS_SetHostPromiseRejectionTracker

    NAME
	QJS_SetHostPromiseRejectionTracker -- Register a callback
	    invoked when promise rejections go unhandled.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetHostPromiseRejectionTracker(rt, cb, opaque)
					   A0  A1  A2

	VOID QJS_SetHostPromiseRejectionTracker(JSRuntime *rt,
		JSHostPromiseRejectionTracker *cb, APTR opaque);

    FUNCTION
	The engine calls `cb(ctx, promise, reason, is_handled,
	opaque)` whenever a rejection is (un)handled.  The host
	typically uses this to log unhandled rejections.

    INPUTS
	rt     - The runtime.
	cb     - Callback, or NULL to disable.
	opaque - User pointer.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_NewPromiseCapability


quickjs.library/QJS_IsJobPending                 quickjs.library/QJS_IsJobPending

    NAME
	QJS_IsJobPending -- Test whether microtasks are waiting to
	    run.

    SYNOPSIS
	result = QJS_IsJobPending(rt)
	D0                        A0

	BOOL QJS_IsJobPending(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	Returns TRUE if there is at least one pending microtask
	(promise reaction, finalizer) queued on the runtime.
	FALSE means the event loop can safely sleep.

    INPUTS
	rt - The runtime.

    RESULT
	result - TRUE or FALSE.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_ExecutePendingJob, QJS_StdLoop


quickjs.library/QJS_ExecutePendingJob         QJS_ExecutePendingJob

    NAME
	QJS_ExecutePendingJob -- Run one pending microtask.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_ExecutePendingJob(rt, pctx)
	D0                         A0  A1

	LONG QJS_ExecutePendingJob(JSRuntime *rt,
				   JSContext **pctx);

    FUNCTION
	Pulls the next queued microtask and runs it.  On entry
	*pctx may be anything; on return it holds the context in
	which the job ran (useful for dumping errors with
	QJS_StdDumpError()).

    INPUTS
	rt   - The runtime.
	pctx - Output pointer for the job's context.

    RESULT
	rc - 1 if a job ran, 0 if the queue was empty, -1 if the
	     job threw an exception (check *pctx for the
	     exception).

    EXAMPLE
	JSContext *ctx1;
	int err;
	do {
	    err = QJS_ExecutePendingJob(rt, &ctx1);
	    if (err < 0) QJS_StdDumpError(ctx1);
	} while (err != 0);

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_IsJobPending, QJS_StdLoop


quickjs.library/QJS_SetCanBlock                   quickjs.library/QJS_SetCanBlock

    NAME
	QJS_SetCanBlock -- Configure whether Atomics.wait() is
	    allowed.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetCanBlock(rt, can_block)
			A0  D0

	VOID QJS_SetCanBlock(JSRuntime *rt, BOOL can_block);

    FUNCTION
	When FALSE, calls to Atomics.wait() throw a TypeError.
	The default is FALSE on AmigaOS since the library is
	single-tasked.

    INPUTS
	rt	  - The runtime.
	can_block - TRUE to allow Atomics.wait(), FALSE to forbid.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AddTypedArrays


quickjs.library/QJS_SetModuleLoaderFunc       QJS_SetModuleLoaderFunc

    NAME
	QJS_SetModuleLoaderFunc -- Install module resolver/loader.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetModuleLoaderFunc(rt, normalize_func, loader_func,
				opaque)
				A0  A1              A2
				A3

	VOID QJS_SetModuleLoaderFunc(JSRuntime *rt,
		JSModuleNormalizeFunc *normalize_func,
		JSModuleLoaderFunc *loader_func, APTR opaque);

    FUNCTION
	Registers callbacks that locate and load modules.  The
	normalizer converts a relative module name into a
	canonical form; the loader reads the module source and
	returns it.

	By default, the library supplies loaders that read
	modules from disk using AmigaOS path conventions
	(incl. "RAM:main.js" volume-relative paths).  Call this
	only to override them.

    INPUTS
	rt	       - The runtime.
	normalize_func - Normalizer callback, or NULL for default.
	loader_func    - Loader callback, or NULL for default.
	opaque	       - Passed to both callbacks.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_LoadModule, QJS_SetModuleLoader


quickjs.library/QJS_SetModuleLoader             QJS_SetModuleLoader

    NAME
	QJS_SetModuleLoader -- Install the library's default
	    module loader.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_SetModuleLoader(rt)
			    A0

	VOID QJS_SetModuleLoader(JSRuntime *rt);

    FUNCTION
	Convenience wrapper that calls QJS_SetModuleLoaderFunc()
	with the library's built-in AmigaOS-aware loader.  This
	loader understands volume-relative paths like
	"RAM:foo.js" and uses dos.library Open() for file reads.

	Normally called once per runtime during init.

    INPUTS
	rt - The runtime.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetModuleLoaderFunc, QJS_LoadModule


quickjs.library/QJS_LoadModule                     quickjs.library/QJS_LoadModule

    NAME
	QJS_LoadModule -- Load and evaluate a module by name.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_LoadModule(result, ctx, basename, filename)
		       A0      A1   A2        A3

	VOID QJS_LoadModule(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			    CONST_STRPTR basename,
			    CONST_STRPTR filename);

    FUNCTION
	Runs the module-loader pipeline on `filename`, resolving
	relative paths against `basename`.  Stores the resulting
	module namespace object in *result.  Equivalent to
	`import()` from JavaScript code.

    INPUTS
	result	 - Output JSValue (module namespace).
	ctx	 - Host context.
	basename - Path of the importing module, or "." for the
		   working directory.
	filename - Module specifier.

    RESULT
	None.

    EXAMPLE
	JSValue mod;
	QJS_LoadModule(&mod, ctx, ".", "./mymodule.js");
	JSValue hello;
	QJS_GetPropertyStr(&hello, ctx, &mod, "hello");
	/* call hello... */

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetModuleLoader, QJS_GetModuleNamespace


quickjs.library/QJS_GetImportMeta               quickjs.library/QJS_GetImportMeta

    NAME
	QJS_GetImportMeta -- Retrieve a module's import.meta
	    object.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetImportMeta(result, ctx, m)
			  A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_GetImportMeta(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
			       JSModuleDef *m);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the `import.meta` object of the given module.
	Typically used by a module loader to populate
	`import.meta.url` before the module evaluates.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	m      - Module definition.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_SetModuleLoaderFunc, QJS_NewCModule


quickjs.library/QJS_GetModuleName               quickjs.library/QJS_GetModuleName

    NAME
	QJS_GetModuleName -- Get a module's canonical name as an
	    atom.

    SYNOPSIS
	atom = QJS_GetModuleName(ctx, m)
	D0                       A0   A1

	JSAtom QJS_GetModuleName(JSContext *ctx, JSModuleDef *m);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the atom holding the module's resolved file name.
	Caller must release with QJS_FreeAtom().

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.
	m   - Module definition.

    RESULT
	atom - Module name atom.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AtomToString, QJS_FreeAtom


quickjs.library/QJS_GetModuleNamespace       QJS_GetModuleNamespace

    NAME
	QJS_GetModuleNamespace -- Get a module's namespace object.

    SYNOPSIS
	QJS_GetModuleNamespace(result, ctx, m)
			       A0      A1   A2

	VOID QJS_GetModuleNamespace(JSValue *result, JSContext *ctx,
				    JSModuleDef *m);

    FUNCTION
	Returns the namespace object (the one you get from
	`import * as NS from ...`) that exposes the module's
	exports.  The module must already be evaluated.

    INPUTS
	result - Output JSValue.
	ctx    - Host context.
	m      - Module definition.

    RESULT
	None.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_LoadModule, QJS_GetModuleName


quickjs.library/QJS_NewCModule                     quickjs.library/QJS_NewCModule

    NAME
	QJS_NewCModule -- Register a native C module.

    SYNOPSIS
	m = QJS_NewCModule(ctx, name_str, func)
	D0                 A0   A1        A2

	JSModuleDef *QJS_NewCModule(JSContext *ctx,
				    CONST_STRPTR name_str,
				    JSModuleInitFunc *func);

    FUNCTION
	Declares a module named `name_str` whose exports are
	installed by the C function `func` when the module is
	evaluated.  After this call, register exports via
	QJS_AddModuleExport() / QJS_AddModuleExportList(),
	then set their values inside `func` via
	QJS_SetModuleExport() / QJS_SetModuleExportList().

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	name_str - Module name (used by `import` specifiers).
	func	 - Init callback of type
		     int (*)(JSContext *, JSModuleDef *).

    RESULT
	m - Opaque module pointer (caller does not free).

    EXAMPLE
	static int my_module_init(JSContext *ctx, JSModuleDef *m) {
	    QJS_SetModuleExport(ctx, m, "answer", &answer_val);
	    return 0;
	}
	JSModuleDef *m = QJS_NewCModule(ctx, "mymodule",
					 my_module_init);
	QJS_AddModuleExport(ctx, m, "answer");

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AddModuleExport, QJS_SetModuleExport


quickjs.library/QJS_AddModuleExport           QJS_AddModuleExport

    NAME
	QJS_AddModuleExport -- Declare a single module export.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_AddModuleExport(ctx, m, name_str)
	D0                       A0   A1 A2

	LONG QJS_AddModuleExport(JSContext *ctx, JSModuleDef *m,
				 CONST_STRPTR name_str);

    FUNCTION
	Adds `name_str` to the list of names exported by the
	module.  Must be called (for every export) between
	QJS_NewCModule() and the module's evaluation.  Set the
	value later via QJS_SetModuleExport().

    INPUTS
	ctx	 - Host context.
	m	 - Module from QJS_NewCModule().
	name_str - Exported name.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on failure.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AddModuleExportList, QJS_SetModuleExport


quickjs.library/QJS_AddModuleExportList     QJS_AddModuleExportList

    NAME
	QJS_AddModuleExportList -- Declare many module exports
	    at once.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_AddModuleExportList(ctx, m, tab, len)
	D0                           A0   A1 A2   D0

	LONG QJS_AddModuleExportList(JSContext *ctx, JSModuleDef *m,
				     const JSCFunctionListEntry *tab,
				     int len);

    FUNCTION
	Bulk-declares exports using the same JSCFunctionListEntry
	array that you later pass to QJS_SetModuleExportList().

    INPUTS
	ctx - Host context.
	m   - Module.
	tab - Entry array.
	len - Count.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on failure.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AddModuleExport, QJS_SetModuleExportList


quickjs.library/QJS_SetModuleExport           QJS_SetModuleExport

    NAME
	QJS_SetModuleExport -- Set the value of a module export.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SetModuleExport(ctx, m, export_name, val_ptr)
	D0                       A0   A1 A2           A3

	LONG QJS_SetModuleExport(JSContext *ctx, JSModuleDef *m,
				 CONST_STRPTR export_name,
				 const JSValue *val_ptr);

    FUNCTION
	Sets the value of the previously-declared export
	`export_name`.  Takes ownership of *val_ptr.  Called from
	the module init function registered with
	QJS_NewCModule().

    INPUTS
	ctx	    - Host context.
	m	    - Module.
	export_name - Name declared via QJS_AddModuleExport().
	val_ptr	    - Pointer to the value.

    RESULT
	rc - 0 on success, non-zero on failure.

    SEE ALSO
	QJS_AddModuleExport, QJS_SetModuleExportList


quickjs.library/QJS_SetModuleExportList     QJS_SetModuleExportList

    NAME
	QJS_SetModuleExportList -- Set many module export values
	    at once.

    SYNOPSIS
	rc = QJS_SetModuleExportList(ctx, m, tab, len)
	D0                           A0   A1 A2   D0

	LONG QJS_SetModuleExportList(JSContext *ctx, JSModuleDef *m,
				     const JSCFunctionListEntry *tab,
				     int len);

    FUNCTION
	Bulk-sets values using the same JSCFunctionListEntry
	array previously passed to
	QJS_AddModuleExportList().

